]\n| [[Sofyan Djalil]] \n|-\n| [[File:Juliari Peter Batubara.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Social Affairs (Indonesia)|Minister of Social Affairs]]\n| [[Juliari Batubara]] \n|-\n| [[File:Official Portrait of Fachrul Razi.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Religious Affairs (Indonesia)|Minister of Religious Affairs]]\n| [[Fachrul Razi]] \n|-\n| [[File:Johnny G. Plate.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Communication and Information Technology (Indonesia)|Minister of Communication and Information Technology]]\n| [[Johnny G. Plate]] \n|-\n| [[File:Menkeu Bambang Brodjonegoro.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Research, Technology and Higher Education (Indonesia)|Minister of Research and Technology]]\n| [[Bambang Brodjonegoro]] \n|-\n| [[File:Teten Masduki 2019.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Cooperatives and Small and Medium Enterprises (Indonesia)|Minister of Cooperatives and Small & Medium Enterprises]]\n| [[Teten Masduki]] \n|-\n| [[File:Menteri Pemberdayaan Perempuan dan Perlindungan Anak, I Gusti Ayu Bintang Darmawati.png|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Women Empowerment and Child Protection|Minister of Women's Empowerment and Child Protection]]\n| [[I Gusti Ayu Bintang Darmawati]] \n|-\n| [[File:Menteri PAN-RB Tjahjo Kumolo.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Administrative and Bureaucratic Reform (Indonesia)|Minister of Administrative and Bureaucratic Reform]]\n| [[Tjahjo Kumolo]] \n|-\n| [[File:Mendes PDTT (2019-2024).jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Villages, Development of Disadvantaged Regions, and Transmigration|Minister of Villages, Development of Disadvantaged Regions and Transmigration]]\n| [[Abdul Halim Iskandar]] \n|-\n| [[File:Suharso Monoarfa.png|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of National Development Planning of Indonesia|Minister of National Development Planning]]\n| [[Suharso Monoarfa]] \n|-\n| [[File:Menteri BUMN Erick Thohir.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of State Owned Enterprises (Indonesia)|Minister of State-Owned Enterprises]]\n| [[Erick Thohir]] \n|-\n| [[File:Wishnutama.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Tourism (Indonesia)|Minister of Tourism and Creative Economy]] ([[Head of Tourism and Creative Economy Agency]])\n| [[Wishnutama]] \n|-\n| [[File:Zainudin Amali DPR.jpg|100px]]\n| [[Ministry of Youth and Sports (Indonesia)|Minister of Youth and Sports]]\n| [[Zainudin Amali]] \n|}\n\n==Predicted and scheduled events==\n*July \u2013 scheduled date for the [[Indonesia 2020 census]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n* January 1 - At least 66 people were killed after [[2020 Jakarta floods|a massive flooding]] swept the Indonesian capital Jakarta. Dubbed as one of the worst floods in Jakarta history, the massive flood was caused by the highest recorded rainfall in 24 years since record began in Jakarta.<ref>{{cite web|author=Damarjati, Danu|title=Jabodetabek Banjir, Curah Hujan 1 Januari 2020 Tertinggi Selama 24 Tahun|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4843412/jabodetabek-banjir-curah-hujan-1-januari-2020-tertinggi-selama-24-tahun|publisher=Detik|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=66 People Have Died in Indonesia's Devastating Floods. Here's What to Know|url=https://time.com/5761097/jakarta-indonesia-floods/|publisher=Time|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n* January 6 - Indonesia announced that it was mobilizing fishermen and naval vessels to patrol the northern part of the [[Natuna Sea]], following incursions by Chinese vessels.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-china/indonesia-deploys-fighter-jets-in-stand-off-with-china-idUSKBN1Z61AM |title=Indonesia deploys fighter jets in stand-off with China |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=January 7, 2020 |first=Stanley |last=Widianto |first2=Agustinus |last2=Beo Da Costa |first3=Wilda |last3=Asmarini |editor-first=Matthew |editor-last=Tostevin |editor-first2=Gareth |editor-last2=Jones}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3045051/chinese-coastguard-ships-sail-tensions-indonesia-build |newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |title=Chinese coastguard ships sail as tensions with Indonesia build |first=Kristin |last=Huang |date=January 7, 2020 |quote=Two Chinese coastguard ships left Fiery Cross Reef in the disputed South China Sea and sailed in the direction of the Indonesia-controlled Natuna Regency islands on Monday, amid renewed tensions between Beijing and Jakarta [...] One of the two ships, CCG 35111, put in at Fiery Cross \u2013 where China has refuel and resupply facilities \u2013 on Saturday |archive-url=https://archive.today/yUXer |archive-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* January 10 - The Indonesian Ministry of Forestry and Environment announced the termination of partnership with WWF due to alleged \"untrue facts and data\" claimed by the WWF.<ref>{{cite web|title=KLHK Putuskan Kerja Sama dengan WWF, Ini Alasannya|url=https://www.liputan6.com/bisnis/read/4166143/klhk-putuskan-kerja-sama-dengan-wwf-ini-alasannya|publisher=Liputan6|accessdate=15 February 2020|date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n* January 14 - Demonstrations took place in front of Jakarta City Hall. Opposition groups demanded the Governor of Jakarta [[Anies Baswedan]] to step down from his position due to the perceived mishandling of the emergency response in the 2020 Jakarta floods while supporters of Anies Baswedan also held two demonstrations to defend the incumbent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Demo Pro & Kontra Anies Sama-Sama Jadikan Banjir Komoditas Politik|url=https://tirto.id/demo-pro-kontra-anies-sama-sama-jadikan-banjir-komoditas-politik-esQX|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n* January 15 - Fictional kingdoms and mythical movements regarded by the government as deceitful acts towards Indonesians began to sprang up across the country.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ramdhani, Jabbar|title=Kerajaan Fiktif Bermunculan di RI, Ada Fenomena Apa Sih?|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4864376/kerajaan-fiktif-bermunculan-di-ri-ada-fenomena-apa-sih|publisher=Detik|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> \n* January 17 - The \"King\" and the \"Queen\" of the Indonesian mythical kingdom \"[[Keraton Agung Sejagat]]\", located in Purworejo, were arrested for public deception.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ditangkap, 'Raja-RAtu' Keraton Agung Sejagat Dijerat Pasal Penipuan|url=https://news.detik.com/berita-jawa-tengah/d-4859279/ditangkap-raja-ratu-keraton-agung-sejagat-dijerat-pasal-penipuan|publisher=Detik|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n* January 28 - Leader of \"Sunda Empire\", Ki Ageng Rangga, was arrested in Bekasi for alleged disinformation and public deception. The organisation \"Sunda Empire\" was later disbanded by the government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Petinggi Sunda Empire Ditangkap di Tambun Saat Mampir ke Rumah Saudaranya|url=https://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2020/01/29/22101651/petinggi-sunda-empire-ditangkap-di-tambun-saat-mampir-ke-rumah-saudaranya|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n* January 29 - Outbreak of dengue fever led to the issuance of declaration of emergency by the government of Sikka, East Nusa Tenggara<ref>{{citeweb|title=Jumlah Penderita DBD Terus Meningkat, Bupati Sikka Tetapkan KLB|url=https://regional.kompas.com/read/2020/01/29/10263981/jumlah-penderita-dbd-terus-meningkat-bupati-sikka-tetapkan-klb|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n* January 30 - Henchman of the leader of a mythical movement called as \"King of The King\" was arrested for alleged public deception.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ferdinan|title=Kaki Tangan Ditangkap, Presiden King of The King Mr Dony Pedro Dicari|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4879052/kaki-tangan-ditangkap-presiden-king-of-the-king-mr-dony-pedro-dicari|publisher=Detik|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n*January 31 \u2013 The Indonesian government expels American journalist Philip Myrer Jacobson of ''Mongabay,'' an environmental science news site, after spending ten days in jail for not having a journalist's visa. At least eight journalists have been deported since 2017.<ref>[https://apnews.com/f20089e9d04b0977a3f5b40f2dade06b Indonesia deports American journalist over visa regulations] by NINIEK KARMINI, Associated Press, 31 Jan 2020</ref>\n\n=== February ===\n[[File:High level meeting on evacuation of Indonesians from Wuhan.png|thumb|A high level meeting was held in Halim Perdanakusuma Airport, Jakarta to discuss on the evacuation of Indonesians from Wuhan]]\n* February 1 - Anger and protests in Natuna as Indonesian government revealed plans to evacuate Indonesian citizens from Wuhan, the centre of a deadly pneumonia outbreak, to Raden Sadjad AFB in Natuna<ref>{{cite web|title=Ratusan Warga Natuna Demo Tolak Karantina WNI dari Wuhan|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200201155027-20-470721/ratusan-warga-natuna-demo-tolak-karantina-wni-dari-wuhan|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 2\n** 238 Indonesians were successfully evacuated to Natuna from virus-hit city [[Wuhan]]. The Indonesian government had planned to evacuate Indonesians in Wuhan after a massive [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|outbreak in China]] caused a global health emergency, infecting thousands and killing hundreds of people.<ref>{{cite web|title=245 WNI dari Wuhan Tiba di Indonesia, Ini Tahapan Evakuasi sampai Isolasi|url=https://www.kompas.com/tren/read/2020/02/02/102259165/245-wni-dari-wuhan-tiba-di-indonesia-ini-tahapan-evakuasi-sampai-isolasi|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n** Indonesian government temporarily halts the issuance of its visa-free policy and visa on arrival for all tourists from China. All flights from and to Mainland China are banned due to concern on the outbreak, effective by 5 February. Those who had been to Mainland China for 14 days during the outbreak would not be allowed to enter or transit in Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Virus corona: Pemerintah tidak izinkan semua pendatang dari China masuk dan transit di Indonesia|url=https://www.bbc.com/indonesia/indonesia-51346574|publisher=BBC Indonesia|accessdate=3 February 2020|newspaper=BBC News Indonesia|date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n* February 5 - An Indonesian maid in Singapore becomes the first confirmed Indonesian to have contracted the [[COVID-19]] disease.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adyatama, Egi|title=WNI Positif Corona di Singapura Dirawat Sebelum Dievakuasi|url=https://nasional.tempo.co/read/1303929/wni-positif-corona-di-singapura-dirawat-sebelum-dievakuasi|publisher=Tempo|accessdate=15 February 2020|date=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n* February 10 - The wreckage of an Indonesian Air Force military helicopter which had disappeared since June 2019 has been found on the mountainous region in Papua. All 12 passengers and crews were killed in the crash.<ref>{{cite web|author=Saiman|title=Helikopter TNI MI-17 yang Hilang Juni 2019 Akhirnya Ditemukan|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4893532/helikopter-tni-mi-17-yang-hilang-juni-2019-akhirnya-ditemukan|publisher=Detik|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 11 - The Indonesian government refuses to repatriate 689 Indonesian citizens that had joined the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] from Syria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pemerintah Putuskan Tak Akan Pulangkan WNI eks ISIS|url=https://www.voaindonesia.com/a/pemerintah-putuskan-tak-akan-pulangkan-wni-eks-isis/5283311.html|publisher=VOA Indonesia|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 12 - A riot erupted in Kabanjahe Detention Centre in Medan. Buildings were reportedly burned by inmates.<ref>{{cite web|title=5 Fakta Baru Kerusuhan di Rutan Kabanjahe, Berawal dari 4 Tahanan yang Kedapatan Miliki Narkotika|url=https://regional.kompas.com/read/2020/02/13/06430061/5-fakta-baru-kerusuhan-di-rutan-kabanjahe-berawal-dari-4-tahanan-yang?page=all|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 15 \n** A total of 238 Indonesians were allowed to go home after being quarantined by the Indonesian government in Natuna in response to the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WNI Pulang dari Natuna: Kami Semua Sehat, Tak Ada yang Kena Virus Corona|url=https://www.suara.com/news/2020/02/15/193411/wni-pulang-dari-natuna-kami-semua-sehat-tak-ada-yang-kena-virus-corona|publisher=Suara|accessdate=15 February 2020|date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n** Residents evacuated after reports of radioactive leak at a residence housing employees of the Indonesian National Nuclear Energy Agency (BATAN) in South Tangerang<ref>{{cite web|title=Perumahan Terpapar Radiasi Nuklir di Serpong, Bapeten Sebut Belum Tentu karena Kebocoran|url=https://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2020/02/15/09421181/perumahan-terpapar-radiasi-nuklir-di-serpong-bapeten-sebut-belum-tentu|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 16 - Indonesia won the [[2020 Badminton Asia Team Championships]] in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web|author=Raya, Mercy|title=Indonesia Juara di Kejuaraan Bulutangkis Beregu Asia 2020|url=https://sport.detik.com/raket/d-4901525/indonesia-juara-di-kejuaraan-bulutangkis-beregu-asia-2020?tag_from=wp_cb_mostPopular_list&_ga=2.105321027.1594699074.1581771686-1646281847.1575295549|publisher=Detik|accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 18 - Three Indonesian crew members of the [[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]] cruise ship were [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships#Diamond Princess|tested positive for coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Sebayang, Rehia|title=Alert! 3 WNI Positif Corona di Kapal Pesiar Diamond Princess|url=https://www.cnbcindonesia.com/news/20200218133518-4-138670/alert-3-wni-positif-corona-di-kapal-pesiar-diamond-princess|publisher=CNBC Indonesia|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 21 - A total of 257 scout members consisting of grade 7 and grade 8 students were swept away during a river expedition in Sleman, Yogyakarta after a flash flood struck the area. At least 10 girl scouts were killed, with age ranging from 12-15 years old. A further 26 scout members were injured. Several people were charged for negligence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Siswa SMPN Turi 1 Korban Tewas Susur Sungai Jadi 10 Orang|url=https://regional.kompas.com/read/2020/02/23/09404561/siswa-smpn-turi-1-korban-tewas-susur-sungai-jadi-10-orang?page=all|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 24 - The Indonesian Ministry of Health announced that a total of 9 Indonesian crew members of the Diamond Princess cruise ship have contracted the COVID-19 disease.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bertambah, WNI di Diamond Princess yang Positif Corona jadi 9 Orang|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/02/24/14425801/bertambah-wni-di-diamond-princess-yang-positif-corona-jadi-9-orang|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 25 - Hundreds evacuated after a second massive flood swept Jakarta in less than two months.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jakarta Banjir Lagi Hari Ini, Terparah Capai 3 Meter hingga Lebih dari 100 Sekolah Terpaksa Libur|url=https://www.tribunnews.com/metropolitan/2020/02/25/jakarta-banjir-lagi-hari-ini-terparah-capai-3-meter-hingga-lebih-dari-100-sekolah-terpaksa-libur|publisher=Tribun News|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 26 - Indonesian government spent Rp 10.3 trillion rupiah (US$744 million) to influencers in hopes of attracting tourists who were scared off by the coronavirus pandemic. <ref>{{cite web|author=Tambun, Lenny Tristia|title=Indonesia to Spend $744m to Woo Tourists Scared Off by Coronavirus|url=https://jakartaglobe.id/business/indonesia-to-spend-744m-to-woo-tourists-scared-off-by-coronavirus|publisher=Jakarta Globe|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n* February 27 \n** Talks are being held as Saudi Arabia temporarily bans the Islamic pilgrimage of Umrah amid efforts to contain the coronavirus pandemic, which has spread to dozens of countries around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indonesia Tak Menyerah Usai Arab Saudi Larang Umroh|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4917942/indonesia-tak-menyerah-usai-arab-saudi-larang-umroh|publisher=Detik|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n** A total of 188 crew members of the World Dream cruise ship were evacuated by the government to KRI dr. Soeharso. They would undergo a 14-day quarantine at Sebaru Kecil Island, Thousands Islands for possible coronavirus infection.<ref>{{citeweb|author=Hamdi, Imam|title=5 Fakta Penjemputan WNI dari Kapal World Dream ke Sebaru|url=https://metro.tempo.co/read/1312804/5-fakta-penjemputan-wni-dari-kapal-world-dream-ke-sebaru/full&view=ok|publisher=Tempo|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n[[File:Erupsi Merapi 3 Maret 2020.jpg|thumb|Eruption of Mount Merapi on 3 March 2020, seen from Babadan, Magelang, Central Java]]\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indonesia}}\n* March 2 - President [[Joko Widodo]] confirmed the first two cases of coronavirus in the country. According to the Minister of Health [[Terawan Agus Putranto]], the patients contracted the virus from an infected Japanese person in Depok and later tested positive in Malaysia. Both are hospitalized in North Jakarta.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4921528/2-wni-positif-virus-corona-dirawat-di-rspi-sulianti-saroso-jakut|title=2 WNI Positif Virus Corona Dirawat di RSPI Sulianti Saroso Jakut|author=Andhika Prasetia|date=2 March 2020|language=id|website=Detik.com}}</ref>\n* March 3 - Mount Merapi erupted, sending ash as high as 6,000 meters to the sky and causing ashfall in Boyolali and neighboring regencies.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Gunung Merapi Meletus Pagi Ini, Erupsi Masih Didominasi Gas|url=https://tirto.id/gunung-merapi-meletus-pagi-ini-erupsi-masih-didominasi-gas-eCA5|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 4 - Government officials confirmed that another two people had been infected with the SARS-CoV-2 virus, raising the number of the infected to 4.<ref>{{citeweb|author=Jarot Bayu, Dimas|title=Pasien Positif Virus Corona di Indonesia Bertambah Jadi 4 Orang|url=https://katadata.co.id/berita/2020/03/06/pasien-positif-virus-corona-di-indonesia-bertambah-jadi-4-orang|publisher=Katadata|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 5 - The Indonesian government decided to forbid the entry of tourists from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|Iran]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]], which at the time were the center of the coronavirus pandemic outside China.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Virus corona: Indonesia melarang warga asing dari Iran, Italia, dan Korsel kunjungi dan transit ke Indonesia|url=https://www.bbc.com/indonesia/indonesia-51749229|publisher=BBC Indonesia|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 8 - A total of 6 people had been infected by the coronavirus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kasus Covid-19 di Indonesia Bertambah 2, Total 6 Orang Positif|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/08/16264851/kasus-covid-19-di-indonesia-bertambah-2-total-6-orang-positif|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 9 \n** Number of people infected by the SARS-CoV-2 virus has jumped to 19.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pasien Positif Corona di Indonesia Bertambah Jadi 19 Orang|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200309172719-20-481849/pasien-positif-corona-di-indonesia-bertambah-jadi-19-orang|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n** At least 7 people were killed and another 20 were rescued after two boats carrying members of [[Presidential Security Force of Indonesia]] collided in Palangkaraya, Central Kalimantan. The collision caused the cancellation of [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|King Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands]] and [[Queen M\u00e1xima of the Netherlands]]'s visit to Central Kalimantan, who at the time were visiting Indonesia.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Tabrakan Speedboat 7 Orang Tewas, Raja & Ratu Belanda Batal ke TN Sebangau|url=https://www.mongabay.co.id/2020/03/10/tabrakan-speedboat-7-orang-tewas-raja-ratu-belanda-batal-ke-tn-sebangau/|publisher=Mongabay|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 10 \n** An earthquake measuring 5.0 magnitude struck [[Sukabumi]], [[West Java]] at a shallow depth of 10 km, causing damages to at least 200 homes. At least 3 people were injured and 300 people were evacuated due to the quake.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Gempa Sukabumi Rusak 202 Rumah, 3 Luka, 173 Mengungsi|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200311063755-20-482303/gempa-sukabumi-rusak-202-rumah-3-luka-173-mengungsi|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Government officials confirmed another 8 cases of the coronavirus, bringing the number of infections to 27.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Jumlah Bertambah, 27 Pasien di Indonesia Positif Corona|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200310175557-20-482202/jumlah-bertambah-27-pasien-di-indonesia-positif-corona|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 11 \n** The Jakarta Formula E was postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Formula E di Monas Resmi Ditunda Akibat Virus Corona|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4933892/formula-e-di-monas-resmi-ditunda-akibat-virus-corona|publisher=Detik News|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n** A British national who had been tested positive for coronavirus has died in [[Bali]], making it the first coronavirus-linked fatality in the country. Another 7 cases of the virus were also confirmed by officials, raising the total number of people infected with the virus to 34.<ref>{{citeweb|title=British tourist dies in Bali from COVID-19, Indonesian authorities under pressure over coronavirus response|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-12/indonesia-coronavirus-death-confirmed-as-british-tourist/12047798|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Indonesian [[Ministry of Manpower (Indonesia)|Minister of Manpower]] Ida Fauziah ordered companies in Indonesia to provide face masks and hand sanitizers to prevent the spread of the coronavirus<ref>{{citeweb|title=Menaker Wajibkan Perusahaan Sediakan Masker bagi Pekerja untuk Cegah Virus Corona|url=https://ternate.tribunnews.com/2020/03/11/menaker-wajibkan-perusahaan-sediakan-masker-bagi-pekerja-untuk-cegah-virus-corona|publisher=Tribun Ternate|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13\n** Cases of COVID-19 in the nation jumps to 69<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kasus Positif Corona di RI Jadi 69|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4938023/kasus-positif-corona-di-ri-jadi-69|publisher=Detik|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n** A total of 1,216 people has been infected with dengue fever in [[Sikka Regency|Sikka]], [[East Nusa Tenggara]]<ref>{{citeweb|title=1.216 Orang Terjangkit, Ini Alasan Angka DBD di Sikka, NTT Tertinggi|url=https://www.kompas.com/sains/read/2020/03/13/082300323/1.216-orang-terjangkit-ini-alasan-angka-dbd-di-sikka-ntt-tertinggi|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n** First death of an Indonesian citizen caused by the coronavirus was confirmed by officials. A man in his 50s has died at a hospital in [[Surakarta|Solo]], [[Central Java]].<ref>{{citeweb|title=Warga Solo Meninggal Positif Corona, 62 Orang Dikarantina Mandiri|url=https://www.merdeka.com/peristiwa/warga-solo-meninggal-positif-corona-62-orang-dikarantina-mandiri.html|publisher=Merdeka|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 14 \n** The number of people who were infected by the SARS-CoV-2 virus has jumped to 96<ref>{{citeweb|title=Update Corona 14 Maret: 96 Positif, 5 Meninggal, 8 Sembuh|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200314160309-20-483417/update-corona-14-maret-96-positif-5-meninggal-8-sembuh|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Minister of Transportation Budi Karya Sumadi has tested positive for the coronavirus<ref>{{citeweb|title=Menhub Budi Karya Positif Corona|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4939379/menhub-budi-karya-positif-corona?tag_from=news_mostpop|publisher=Detik|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The city of Solo declared an emergency over the coronavirus pandemic<ref>{{citeweb|title=Solo KLB Virus Corona, Sekolah Libur 2 Minggu|url=https://www.ayobandung.com/read/2020/03/14/82564/solo-klb-corona-sekolah-libur-2-minggu|publisher=AyoBandung.com|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n** In response to the ongoing coronavirus pandemic, some provinces chose to close schools until indefinite time. Lectures and classes were cancelled and some gatherings were banned<ref>{{citeweb|author=Makdori, Yopi|title=15 Perguruan Tinggi Gelar Kuliah Jarak Jauh, Ini Daftarnya|url=https://www.liputan6.com/news/read/4201718/15-perguruan-tinggi-gelar-kuliah-jarak-jauh-ini-daftarnya|publisher=Liputan6|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n** National disaster declaration as fears of rapidly spreading coronavirus cases grow.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kemenkes: Corona Bencana Nasional, Bukan Darurat Nasional|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4939175/kemenkes-corona-bencana-nasional-bukan-darurat-nasional|publisher=Detik|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 15 - The number of COVID-19 cases rises to 117.<ref>{{citeweb|title=21 Kasus Baru, Pasien Positif Corona Indonesia Jadi 117 Orang|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200315133445-20-483573/21-kasus-baru-pasien-positif-corona-indonesia-jadi-117-orang|publisher=CNN Indonesia}}</ref>\n* March 16 \n** Indonesia confirmed 17 new cases of infection, in total of 134 cases. 14 of new cases in Jakarta, 1 new case in Central Java, 1 new case in Banten, and 1 new case in West Java.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4941340/ada-tambahan-17-pasien-corona-baru-14-di-antaranya-dari-jakarta|title=Ada Tambahan 17 Pasien Corona Baru, 14 di Antaranya dari Jakarta|last=Luxiana|first=Kadek Melda|website=detiknews|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n** Indonesia announced that it will start to quarantine non symptomatic COVID-19 patients on their own home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4941325/kemenkes-sekarang-pasien-positif-corona-bisa-diisolasi-mandiri-di-rumah|title=Kemenkes: Sekarang Pasien Positif Corona Bisa Diisolasi Mandiri di Rumah|last=Melda|first=Kadek|website=detiknews|language=id-ID|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* March 17 - The Indonesian Government announced another 38 new cases of COVID-19, bringing the total number to 172.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Data Terbaru Virus Corona: Total Kasus Positif Melonjak Jadi 172|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4942786/data-terbaru-virus-corona-total-kasus-positif-melonjak-jadi-172|publisher=Detik|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 18 \n** Coronavirus cases rises to 227.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Update Terbaru: Jumlah Pasien Positif Corona Capai 227 Orang|url=https://nasional.tempo.co/read/1321108/update-terbaru-jumlah-pasien-positif-corona-capai-227-orang|publisher=Tempo|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** West Kalimantan declares an emergency due to the ongoing COVID-19 outbreak<ref>{{citeweb|title=Ada 2 Kasus Positif, Gubernur Tetapkan Kalbar KLB Corona|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4944658/ada-2-kasus-positif-gubernur-tetapkan-kalbar-klb-corona|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 19\n** The government announced 81 new cases of COVID-19, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 308 in the country. It also announced that rapid testing tools for the virus would be ordered from China.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pemerintah Meralat: Kasus Positif Corona di RI Jadi 308 Kasus|url=https://www.cnbcindonesia.com/news/20200319182124-4-146252/pemerintah-meralat-kasus-positif-corona-di-ri-jadi-308-kasus|publisher=CNBC Indonesia|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=RI Mau Beli Alat Tes Corona 'Secepat Kilat' Buatan China|url=https://finance.detik.com/berita-ekonomi-bisnis/d-4944943/ri-mau-beli-alat-tes-corona-secepat-kilat-buatan-china|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Regent of Gowa announced that Ijtima Dunia, a [[Tabligh Akbar]] with participants from all over the world, had been cancelled due to concerns that the event might accelerate the rate of coronavirus infections in the province.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Bupati Gowa: Ijtima Dunia Resmi Dibatalkan|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4944944/bupati-gowa-ijtima-dunia-resmi-dibatalkan|publisher=Detik|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 20 \n** Total number of infections rises to 369.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Data Terbaru: 369 Kasus Positif Corona, Meningkat 60 Kasus|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4947188/data-terbaru-369-kasus-positif-corona-meningkat-60-kasus|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Emergency declaration in Jakarta and East Java as numbers of coronavirus infections kept rising<ref>{{citeweb|title=Corona Ancam Jakarta, Anies Tetapkan Status Tanggap Darurat Bencana|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4947518/corona-ancam-jakarta-anies-tetapkan-status-tanggap-darurat-bencana|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=9 Orang Positif Covid-19, Khofifah Tetapkan Jatim Darurat Virus Corona|url=https://regional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/20/18240621/9-orang-positif-covid-19-khofifah-tetapkan-jatim-darurat-virus-corona|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Mayor of Bogor, Bima Arya,<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kronologi Wali Kota Bogor Bima Arya Positif Corona|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200320071543-20-485182/kronologi-wali-kota-bogor-bima-arya-positif-corona|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> and Indonesian actor, Detri Warmanto, has tested positive for the SARS-Cov-2 virus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pemain Film '3 Srikandi', Detri Warmanto Positif Corona|url=https://hot.detik.com/celeb/d-4947822/pemain-film-3-srikandi-detri-warmanto-positif-corona|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** President Joko Widodo announced that the government had ordered 5,000 Avigan ([[Favipiravir]]) and 5 million [[chloroquine]], which were going to be tested to patients who had contracted the coronavirus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Jokowi Pesan Obat Avigan & Klorokuin untuk Dites ke Pasien COVID-19|url=https://tirto.id/jokowi-pesan-obat-avigan-klorokuin-untuk-dites-ke-pasien-covid-19-eGrK|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> He also announced that, starting today on 20 March, mass rapid testings would be conducted on areas with high number of infections.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Deteksi Corona, Pemerintah Mulai Lakukan Rapid Test Hari Ini|url=https://katadata.co.id/berita/2020/03/20/deteksi-corona-pemerintah-mulai-lakukan-rapid-test-hari-ini|publisher=KataData|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 21\n** Number of infections rises to 450.\n** Minister of Defence [[Prabowo Subianto]] ordered the [[Indonesian Armed Forces]] to pick up approximately 9 tonnes of medical equipment in [[Shanghai]], China.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Prabowo Minta TNI Segera Angkut Alat Kesehatan dari China|url=https://www.cnbcindonesia.com/news/20200319192221-4-146277/prabowo-minta-tni-segera-angkut-alat-kesehatan-dari-china|publisher=CNCB Indonesia|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Rising number of coronavirus cases prompted the government to turn Kemayoran's athletes village as a makeshift hospital.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Jadi RS Darurat, Simak Kelayakan Wisma Atlet Jadi Tempat Isolasi Pasien Virus Corona|url=https://economy.okezone.com/read/2020/03/20/470/2186215/jadi-rs-darurat-simak-kelayakan-wisma-atlet-jadi-tempat-isolasi-pasien-virus-corona|publisher=Okezone|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 22\n** Number of infections rises to 514\n** Indonesian actress Andrea Dian has tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Andrea Dian, Artis Indonesia Kedua Positif Corona|url=https://www.tagar.id/andrea-dian-artis-indonesia-kedua-positif-corona|publisher=Tagar|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Governor of West Java [[Ridwan Kamil]] announced that mass rapid testing for the virus would be held on 25 March.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Rapid Test Massal Corona di Jabar Dimulai Pekan Depan|url=https://news.detik.com/berita-jawa-barat/d-4948935/rapid-test-massal-corona-di-jabar-dimulai-pekan-depan|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 23\n[[File:Serah terima peralatan medis dari Republik Rakyat Tiongkok atas pandemi COVID-19.jpg|thumb|Medical supplies were picked up from China in response to the coronavirus outbreak in Indonesia]]\n** Number of coronavirus cases rises to 579.\n** Vice mayor of Bandung Yana Mulyana has tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Wakil Wali Kota Bandung Positif Corona|url=https://news.detik.com/berita-jawa-barat/d-4950593/wakil-wali-kota-bandung-positif-corona|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** President Joko Widodo opened the first makeshift hospital in Kemayoran, Jakarta in response to the ongoing coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Hari Ini, Jokowi Resmikan Wisma Atlet Jadi Rumah Sakit Corona|url=https://nasional.tempo.co/read/1322801/hari-ini-jokowi-resmikan-wisma-atlet-jadi-rumah-sakit-corona|publisher=Tempo|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 24\n** A total of 107 new cases of coronavirus infections were confirmed by the government.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Ada 686 Kasus Positif Corona di 24 Provinsi RI, Ini Sebarannya|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4951605/ada-686-kasus-positif-corona-di-24-provinsi-ri-ini-sebarannya|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The 2020 National Examination has been cancelled due to the outbreak.<ref>{{citeweb|title=BREAKING NEWS: UN 2020 Resmi Dibatalkan|url=https://www.kompas.com/edu/read/2020/03/24/123844371/breaking-news-un-2020-resmi-dibatalkan|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Regent of Karawang Cellica Nurrachdiana has tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Bupati Karawang Positif, Kasus Klaster Corona 'Musda Hipmi' Jadi 6 Orang|url=https://news.detik.com/berita-jawa-barat/d-4951684/bupati-karawang-positif-kasus-klaster-corona-musda-hipmi-jadi-6-orang?tag_from=news_mostpop|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The government announced that it has distributed a total of 125,000 rapid testing kits to all 34 provinces in Indonesia.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pemerintah Distribusikan 125 Ribu Rapid Test Kit Corona ke 34 Provinsi|url=https://20.detik.com/detikflash/20200324-200324058/pemerintah-distribusikan-125-ribu-rapid-test-kit-corona-ke-34-provinsi|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Papua announced that all means of transport from and in to the province would be shut down amid the coronavirus pandemic, effective by 26 March.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Darurat Corona, Akses Keluar-Masuk Papua Ditutup!|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4951923/darurat-corona-akses-keluar-masuk-papua-ditutup/2|publisher=Detik|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 25\n** Numbers of people tested positive with coronavirus has risen to 790.\n** The Indonesian Ministry of Transportation discouraged Indonesians to participate in this year's Eid-al Fitr's annual tradition of [[Mudik]].<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kemenhub Minta Masyarakat Tidak Mudik, Lebaran Bisa Video Call|url=https://finance.detik.com/berita-ekonomi-bisnis/d-4952578/kemenhub-minta-masyarakat-tidak-mudik-lebaran-bisa-video-call?tag_from=wp_beritautama&_ga=2.107555403.834036946.1583960210-317182638.1583477810|publisher=Detik|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 26\n** Coronavirus cases rises to 893 with an increase of 20 deaths, the largest rise since the start of the outbreak in the country.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Update Corona 26 Maret: 893 Kasus, 78 Meninggal, 35 Sembuh|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200326110047-20-486984/update-corona-26-maret-893-kasus-78-meninggal-35-sembuh|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Mayor of [[Tegal]] announced a lockdown on the entire city, starting on 30 March. All means of transport from and in to the city would not be allowed by authorities.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Tegal Lockdown: 49 Jalan Akan Ditutup Beton, Tamu Diisolasi|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200327083557-20-487375/tegal-lockdown-49-jalan-akan-ditutup-beton-tamu-diisolasi|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Fears of thousands of undetected coronavirus infections as Indonesia ranks low in terms of testing for coronavirus detection.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Indonesia\u2019s hidden coronavirus cases threaten to overwhelm hospitals|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/mar/26/indonesia-could-have-thousands-of-hidden-coronavirus-cases-study-says|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 27\n** Number of coronavirus infections tops 1,000 mark.<ref>{{citeweb|title=UPDATE: Pasien Tambah 153, Total Ada 1.046 Kasus Covid-19 di Indonesia|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/27/15530691/update-pasien-tambah-153-total-ada-1046-kasus-covid-19-di-indonesia|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Persib striker [[Wander Luiz]] has tested positive for the coronavirus<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kronologi Striker Persib Wander Luiz Positif Corona|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/olahraga/20200328114710-142-487776/kronologi-striker-persib-wander-luiz-positif-corona|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Mount Merapi erupted for the second time in less than a month, sending ash as high as 5,000 meters to the sky. Ashfall was reported in Magelang, Central Java. It later erupted again in less than 12 hours with an ash column of 1,000 meters.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Fakta 2 Kali Erupsi Gunung Merapi 27 Maret 2020|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparannews/fakta-2-kali-erupsi-gunung-merapi-27-maret-2020-1t6pVcln6WQ|publisher=Kumparan|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 28\n** A total of 109 new cases of coronavirus were confirmed by the government, bringing the number of accumulative cases to 1,155. Total number of deaths has reached 100.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pasien Corona Meninggal di RI Bertambah Jadi 102, Sembuh 59|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4956645/pasien-corona-meninggal-di-ri-bertambah-jadi-102-sembuh-59?tag_from=news_mostpop|publisher=Detik|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n** At least 150 members of a mosque congregation in Kebon Jeruk were quarantined at the mosque after 3 members had tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=78 WNA Ikut Diisolasi di Masjid Jakbar, Ada yang Mengeluh Batuk Pilek|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4956548/78-wna-ikut-diisolasi-di-masjid-jakbar-ada-yang-mengeluh-batuk-pilek?_ga=2.30150392.67030274.1585025580-1646281847.1575295549|publisher=Detik|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* March 29 - Confirmed coronavirus cases rises to 1,285.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pernyataan Lengkap Pemerintah Terkait Update Corona 29 Maret 2020|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4957458/pernyataan-lengkap-pemerintah-terkait-update-corona-29-maret-2020|publisher=Detik|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* March 30\n** Coronavirus cases rises to 1,414\n** Indonesian government announced that coronavirus task force have been set up in all Indonesia's 34 provinces.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pernyataan Lengkap Pemerintah soal Update Corona 30 Maret 2020|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4958626/pernyataan-lengkap-pemerintah-soal-update-corona-30-maret-2020/2|publisher=Detik|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* March 31\n** During an adress to the nation, Indonesian president Joko Widodo announced the implementation of \"Large-scale social restrictions\" (PSBB), which would restrict the mobility of people during the outbreak, adding that electrical fees for 24 million people in Indonesia would be compensated by the government for three months. The government had considered regional quarantine, but later refused and opted for the PSBB.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Pidato Lengkap Jokowi, dari PSBB, Listrik Gratis, hingga Keringanan Kredit|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/03/31/16271751/pidato-lengkap-jokowi-dari-psbb-listrik-gratis-hingga-keringanan-kredit?page=1|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Health emergency has been declared by the government in response to the growing number of coronavirus cases.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Jokowi Tetapkan Darurat Kesehatan Masyarakat, Ini Aturannya|url=https://www.cnbcindonesia.com/news/20200401085950-4-148924/jokowi-tetapkan-darurat-kesehatan-masyarakat-ini-aturannya|publisher=CNBC Indonesia|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n[[File:055260500 1584762616-20200321-Rumah-Sakit-Lapangan-5.jpg|thumb|Field hospitals are being set up in response to the growing number of coronavirus cases]]\n* April 1\n** Indonesia's [[case fatality rate]] remains as one of the highest in the world, as number of deaths rises to 157. Cases of COVID-19 rises to 1,677.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Update Corona 1 April: Sebaran 1.677 Kasus di 32 Provinsi Indonesia|url=https://tirto.id/update-corona-1-april-sebaran-1677-kasus-di-32-provinsi-indonesia-eKdu|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Reports emerged that multiple villagers in Indonesia had refused the burial of coronavirus victims in their villages. Ambulances were reportedly pelted with stones and shouted at.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Ironis, Pemakaman Korban Corona Ditolak dan Ambulans Diusir di Sejumlah Daerah, Mana Saja?|url=https://regional.kompas.com/read/2020/04/01/06000021/ironis-pemakaman-korban-corona-ditolak-dan-ambulans-diusir-di-sejumlah|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Concerns as cases of discrimination towards medical workers, coronavirus patients and suspected coronavirus patients were reported across the nation.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Mati-matian Siang Malam Rawat Pasien Corona, Para Tenaga Medis Ini Diusir dari Rumahnya Sendiri Hingga Kena Julid Tetangga, Netizen: Terang-terangan Diteriakin 'Corona'! |url=https://sosok.grid.id/read/412078301/mati-matian-siang-malam-rawat-pasien-corona-para-tenaga-medis-ini-diusir-dari-rumahnya-sendiri-hingga-kena-julid-tetangga-netizen-terang-terangan-diteriakin-corona?page=all|publisher=Grid|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=Derita Tenaga Medis: Terancam Corona, Kini Diusir dari Tempat Tinggal|url=https://www.vivanews.com/berita/nasional/42551-derita-tenaga-medis-terancam-corona-kini-diusir-dari-tempat-tinggal|publisher=Viva News|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=Kisah Buruh Saat Wabah Corona, Diusir dari Kontrakan Hingga Jadi Pemulung|url=https://banten.suara.com/read/2020/04/05/133805/kisah-buruh-saat-wabah-corona-diusir-dari-kontrakan-hingga-jadi-pemulung|publisher=Suara|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 2\n** Indonesian government announced that at least 30,000 prisoners would be released due to fear of mass outbreak in overcrowded prisons.<ref name=prisoner>{{citeweb|url=https://jakartaglobe.id/news/indonesia-releases-30000-prisoners-as-covid19-cases-double-in-a-week|title=Indonesia Releases 30,000 Prisoners as COVID-19 Cases Double in a Week|author=Nur Yasmin|work=Jakarta Globe|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Outrage as Indonesian Minister for Security and Human Rights, [[Yasonna Laoly]], suggested to release prisoners who had been convicted for corruption. The government later clarified that those who were convicted for corruptions, illegal logging, terrorism, drug crimes, gross human rights crimes or transnational organized crimes would not be released from prison.<ref name=prisoner/>\n** Regent of [[North Morowali Regency|North Morowali]] [[:id:Aptripel_Tumimomor|Aptripel Tumimomor]] has died while being under observation for the coronavirus. He later tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kronologi Meninggalnya Bupati Morowali Utara, Ternyata Positif Covid-19|url=https://health.grid.id/read/352090318/kronologi-meninggalnya-bupati-morowali-utara-ternyata-positif-covid-19?page=all|publisher=Grid|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Mount Merapi erupted with an observed ash column of 3,000 meters. Ashfall was reported in Sleman Regency.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Gunung Merapi Meletus, Hujan Abu Tipis Terjadi di Sleman|url=https://yogyakarta.kompas.com/read/2020/04/02/17240581/gunung-merapi-meletus-hujan-abu-tipis-terjadi-di-sleman|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 3\n** Coronavirus cases in Indonesia rises to 1,986<ref name=3April>{{citeweb|title=Update Corona Indonesia: Kasus Melonjak 196 Jadi 1.986 per 3 April|url=https://tirto.id/update-corona-indonesia-kasus-melonjak-196-jadi-1986-per-3-april-eKEv|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Government spokesman announced that [[tuberculosis]] diagnostic machines would be converted to COVID-19 detection kit.<ref name=3April/>\n** More than 300,000 [[Personal Protective Equipment|PPEs]] had been distributed throughout Indonesia's 34 provinces.<ref name=3April/>\n* April 4 - Coronavirus cases passes 2,000 mark.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Update Corona Indonesia 4 April, Sebaran 2.092 Kasus di 32 Provinsi|url=https://tirto.id/update-corona-indonesia-4-april-sebaran-2092-kasus-di-32-provinsi-eKTY|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n* April 5\n** Cases of coronavirus infections rises to 2,273.<ref name=wajib>{{citeweb|title=Catat, Wajib Pakai Masker Buat Semua Warga RI Mulai Hari Ini!|url=https://www.cnbcindonesia.com/lifestyle/20200405174659-33-149879/catat-wajib-pakai-masker-buat-semua-warga-ri-mulai-hari-ini|publisher=CNBC Indonesia|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Due to the growing number of infections, the Indonesian Government ordered every citizens in Indonesia to wear a mask when in public.<ref name=wajib/>\n* April 6\n** Death toll from the coronavirus outbreak in Indonesia tops 200, the highest deaths in Southeast Asia to date\n** The makeshift hospital in Galang Island, [[Batam]], is officially opened. The hospital will be used to treat coronavirus patients in the country.<ref>{{citeweb|title=RS Darurat Covid-19 di Pulau Galang Resmi Dibuka|url=https://www.beritasatu.com/nasional/617477-rs-darurat-covid19-di-pulau-galang-resmi-dibuka|publisher=Berita Satu|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Government of Jakarta announced that those who didn't use mask in public would not be allowed to board any public transportation.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Wajib Pakai Masker di Angkutan Umum Jakarta Berlaku 12 April|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200406104233-20-490675/wajib-pakai-masker-di-angkutan-umum-jakarta-berlaku-12-april|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> \n* April 7 \n** Government announced 248 new coronavirus cases, the highest rise to date.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Update Corona 7 April 2020 Indonesia & Dunia: Data Terbaru Covid-19|url=https://tirto.id/update-corona-7-april-2020-indonesia-dunia-data-terbaru-covid-19-eLzn|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Ministry of Health granted Jakarta's decision to impose large-scale social restrictions, starting April 10, becoming the first province to implement the program.<ref>{{citeweb|title=COVID-19: Health Ministry grants Jakarta\u2019s request to impose large-scale social restrictions|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/04/07/covid-19-health-ministrygrants-jakartas-request-to-impose-large-scale-social-restrictions.html|publisher=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 8\n** Number of coronavirus infections rises to 2,956 and the death toll rises to 240. 220 people had recovered from the disease.\n** Officials announced that the government would buy 20 diagnostic machines from Swiss company giant [[Hoffmann-La Roche|Roche]]. Each would hold a capacity for 10,000 samples per day and would be distributed to 12 provinces across Indonesia.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Indonesia steps up testing capacity|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-52208591|publisher=BBC|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 9\n** Number of coronavirus cases tops 3,000 \n** Gorontalo confirms its first case, becoming the last province in Indonesia to do so. The coronavirus was confirmed to have spread to all Indonesia's 34 provinces.<ref>{{citeweb|title=1 Kasus Positif di Gorontalo, Seluruh Provinsi di Indonesia Sudah Terpapar Covid-19|url=https://nasional.kompas.com/read/2020/04/10/16483641/1-kasus-positif-di-gorontalo-seluruh-provinsi-di-indonesia-sudah-terpapar|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Ministry of Education announced that the government would provide televised study sessions for all students ranging from kindergarten to high school students on the Indonesian national television channel TVRI.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Mendikbud: Program Belajar dari Rumah Disiarkan TVRI Mulai 13 April|url=https://tirto.id/mendikbud-program-belajar-dari-rumah-disiarkan-tvri-mulai-13-april-eL7Z|publisher=Tirto|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 10\n** Residents of Depok and Jakarta were stunned by a loud explosive sound during the early hours of April 10. Locals speculated that the eruption of Mount Anak Krakatoa in Sunda Strait might have been the cause, but it was later clarified by [[Volcanological Survey of Indonesia]] that the loud boom was caused by thunders in Mount Salak.<ref>{{citeweb|title=PVMBG: Dentuman Misterius yang Terdengar di Jabodetabek Suara Petir dari Gunung Salak|url=https://www.liputan6.com/news/read/4225294/pvmbg-dentuman-misterius-yang-terdengar-di-jabodetabek-suara-petir-dari-gunung-salak|publisher=Liputan6|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Mount Merapi erupted for the second time in more than a week, with an observed ash column of 3,000 meters.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Gunung Merapi Meletus Lagi, Kolom Erupsi Tiga Kilometer|url=https://tekno.tempo.co/read/1330080/gunung-merapi-meletus-lagi-kolom-erupsi-tiga-kilometer|publisher=Tempo|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Mount Anak Krakatoa erupted twice, sending ash as high as 200-500 meters.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Gunung Anak Krakatau Erupsi, Bagaimana Pantauan Terakhir Gunung Merapi?|url=https://www.kompas.com/tren/read/2020/04/11/133124965/gunung-anak-krakatau-erupsi-bagaimana-pantauan-terakhir-gunung-merapi|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 11\n** Ministry of Health approved the implementation of Large-scale mobility restriction (PSBB) in Bogor, Depok, and Bekasi.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Menkes Setuju PSBB Bodebek, Achmad Yurianto: Mulainya Terserah Pemda|url=https://www.inews.id/news/nasional/menkes-setuju-psbb-bodebek-achmad-yurianto-mulainya-terserah-pemda|publisher=iNews|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Indonesian government launched the Indonesian pre-employment card to support those who suffered economic difficulty due to the outbreak of coronavirus.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kartu Prakerja Diluncurkan, OVO Jadi Mitra Resmi Uang Elektronik|url=https://bisnis.tempo.co/read/1330650/kartu-prakerja-diluncurkan-ovo-jadi-mitra-resmi-uang-elektronik|publisher=Tempo|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 12\n** Largest increase of coronavirus cases as government confirmed 399 new cases. Number of coronavirus infections passes 4,000<ref>{{citeweb|title=Virus Corona di Indonesia: 399 Kasus Baru pada 12 April, Penambahan Tertinggi Sejak 2 Maret 2020|url=https://www.kompas.com/tren/read/2020/04/12/212807365/virus-corona-di-indonesia-399-kasus-baru-pada-12-april-penambahan-tertinggi|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Clash between the Indonesian National Armed Forces and Indonesian National Police in Papua killed at least 3 people.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kronologi Bentrok TNI-Polri yang Tewaskan 3 Polisi di Papua|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200412204444-20-492850/kronologi-bentrok-tni-polri-yang-tewaskan-3-polisi-di-papua|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* April 13\n** At least 26 crew members of MV Lambelu were tested positive for the coronavirus<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kadinkes Sulsel: 42 ABK KM Lambelu Sudah Tes Swab, 26 Positif Corona|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4974686/kadinkes-sulsel-42-abk-km-lambelu-sudah-tes-swab-26-positif-corona|publisher=Detik|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Health ministry denied the request for PSBB from three provinces as the condition of the provinces \"didn't meet the criteria\" for implementation.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Menkes Tolak Permohonan PSBB di Sejumlah Daerah, Ini Daftarnya|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4974840/menkes-tolak-permohonan-psbb-di-sejumlah-daerah-ini-daftarnya|publisher=Detik|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Deaths==\n===January===\n*1 January \u2013 [[Chris Pattikawa]], film director and producer (b. 1940).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kompas.com/hype/read/2020/01/01/123841266/sutradara-chris-pattikawa-meninggal-dunia  |title=Sutradara Chris Pattikawa Meninggal Dunia |website=kompas.com |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n*4 January \u2013 [[Gugum Gumbira]], gamelan composer and orchestra leader (b. 1945) <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kompas.com/tren/read/2020/01/05/105600265/mengenang-maestro-jaipongan-gugum-gumbira-tirasondjaja|title=Mengenang Maestro Jaipongan, Gugum Gumbira Tirasondjaja...|lang=id|date=5 January 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*5 January \u2013 [[Mien Sugandhi]], politician (b. 1934).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2020/01/06/former-womens-affairs-minister-mien-sugandhi-dies-at-85.html |title=Former women's affairs minister Mien Sugandhi dies at 85 |website=thejakartapost.com |accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n*6 January \u2013 [[Ria Irawan]], actress (b. 1969).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://en.tempo.co/read/1291515/actress-ria-irawan-passes-away-at-50 |title=Actress Ria Irawan Passes Away at 50 |website=en.tempo.co |accessdate=22 January 2020|date=2020-01-06 }}</ref>\n===February===\n[[File:Salahuddin Wahid, Seminar Nasional Peran Pesantren dalam Pembangunan Kesehatan.jpg|180px|thumb|Salahuddin Wahid]]\n*3 February \u2013 [[Salahuddin Wahid]] (Gus Sholah), scholar and politician (b. 1942)<ref>{{cite web|title=Gus Sholah Meninggal Dunia|url=https://www.kompas.com/tren/read/2020/02/02/213434965/gus-sholah-meninggal-dunia|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n*4 February \u2013 Allan Wangsa, presenter and youtuber (b. 1988)<ref>{{cite web|title=Presenter Allan Wangsa Meninggal Dunia|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparanhits/presenter-allan-wangsa-meninggal-dunia-1smMbr0YC7N|publisher=Kumparan|accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n*20 February \u2013 [[Ashraf Sinclair]], actor (b. 1979)<ref>{{cite web|title=Ashraf Sinclair, Suami BCL Meninggal Dunia |url=https://www.kompas.com/hype/read/2020/02/18/063014666/ashraf-sinclair-suami-bcl-meninggal-dunia|author=Andi Muttya Keteng Pangerang|work=Kompas.com|date=18 February 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n[[File:Sudjiatmi.jpg|120px|thumb|Sudjiatmi Notomihardjo]]\n* 11 March \u2013 Rama Aiphama, singer (b. 1956)<ref>{{citeweb|title=Kabar Duka, Rama Aiphama Meninggal Dunia|url=https://www.kompas.com/hype/read/2020/03/11/103702466/kabar-duka-rama-aiphama-meninggal-dunia?page=all|publisher=Kompas|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 25 March - Sudjiatmi Notomihardjo, Mother of Indonesian President Joko Widodo (b. 1943)<ref>{{citeweb|title=Mengenang Ibunda Jokowi, Ini Profil Sudjiatmi Notomihardjo|url=https://nasional.tempo.co/read/1324003/mengenang-ibunda-jokowi-ini-profil-sudjiatmi-notomihardjo|publisher=Tempo|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 27 March - Imam Suroso, politician (b.1946)<ref>{{citeweb|title=Jejak Imam Suroso Sebelum Meninggal karena Diduga Corona|url=https://www.cnnindonesia.com/nasional/20200328143526-20-487814/jejak-imam-suroso-sebelum-meninggal-karena-diduga-corona|publisher=CNN Indonesia|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n* 27 March - Gatot Tjahyono, politician (b.1962)<ref>{{citeweb|title=Positif Corona, Politikus PDIP Jawa Barat Meninggal|url=https://www.msn.com/id-id/berita/nasional/positif-corona-politikus-pdip-jawa-barat-meninggal/ar-BB11OT6Y|publisher=MSN|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n===April===\n[[File:Glenn Fredly.jpg|120px|thumb|Glenn Fredly]]\n* 2 April - [[:id:Aptripel_Tumimomor|Aptripel Tumimomor]], Regent of [[North Morowali Regency]] (b. 1966)<ref>{{citeweb|title=Bupati Morowali Utara yang Meninggal Dunia Dinyatakan Positif Corona|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-4964665/bupati-morowali-utara-yang-meninggal-dunia-dinyatakan-positif-corona|publisher=Detik|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 8 April - [[Glenn Fredly]], musician (b. 1975)<ref>{{citeweb|title=Glenn Fredly Meninggal Dunia|url=https://www.liputan6.com/showbiz/read/4222975/glenn-fredly-meninggal-dunia|publisher=Liputan6|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Indonesia |Current events|Asia|Modern history}}\n===Country overviews===\n* [[Indonesia ]]\n* [[History of Indonesia ]]\n* [[History of modern Indonesia ]]\n* [[Outline of Indonesia ]]\n* [[Government of Indonesia ]]\n* [[Politics of Indonesia ]]\n\n===Related timelines for current period===\n* [[2020]]\n* [[2020 in politics and government]]\n* [[2020s]]\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Indonesia}}\n{{Year in Asia|2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Indonesia| ]]\n[[Category:2020s in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:2020 in Asia|Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|Indonesia]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarch:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: adress \u2192 address", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_Indonesia"}
{"title_page": "Angiotensin", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox gene}}\n\n'''Angiotensin''' is a [[peptide hormone]] that causes [[vasoconstriction]] and an increase in [[blood pressure]]. It is part of the [[renin\u2013angiotensin system]], which regulates blood pressure. Angiotensin also stimulates the release of [[aldosterone]] from the [[adrenal cortex]] to promote sodium retention by the kidneys.\n\nAn [[peptide|oligopeptide]], angiotensin is a [[hormone]] and a [[dipsogen]]. It is derived from the precursor molecule angiotensinogen, a serum globulin produced in the [[liver]]. Angiotensin was isolated in the late 1930s (first named 'angiotonin' or 'hypertensin') and subsequently characterized and synthesized by groups at the [[Cleveland Clinic]] and [[Ciba Specialty Chemicals|Ciba]] laboratories.<ref name=\"pmid11751697\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Basso N, Terragno NA | title = History about the discovery of the renin-angiotensin system | journal = Hypertension | volume = 38 | issue = 6 | pages = 1246\u20139 | date = December 2001 | pmid = 11751697 | doi = 10.1161/hy1201.101214 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n== Precursor and types ==\n\n=== Angiotensinogen ===\nAngiotensinogen is an [[Alpha globulin|\u03b1-2-globulin]] synthesized in the liver<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hormone.org/your-health-and-hormones/glands-and-hormones-a-to-z/hormones/angiotensin|title=Angiotensin {{!}} Hormone Health Network|website=www.hormone.org|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> and is a precursor for angiotensin, but has also been indicated as having many other roles not related to angiotensin peptides.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=Hong|last2=Cassis|first2=Lisa A.|last3=Kooi|first3=Craig W. Vander|last4=Daugherty|first4=Alan|date=July 2016|title=Structure and functions of angiotensinogen|journal=Hypertension Research|volume=39|issue=7|pages=492\u2013500|doi=10.1038/hr.2016.17|pmid=26888118|pmc=4935807|issn=1348-4214}}</ref> It is a member of the serin family of proteins, leading to another name: Serin A8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P01019|title=AGT - Angiotensinogen precursor - Homo sapiens (Human) - AGT gene & protein|website=www.uniprot.org|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> although it is not known to inhibit other enzymes like most serins. In addition, a generalized crystal structure can be estimated by examining other proteins of the serin family, but angiotensinogen has an elongated N-terminus compared to other serin family proteins.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Streatfeild-James|first=Rosa M. A.|last2=Williamson|first2=David|last3=Pike|first3=Robert N.|last4=Tewksbury|first4=Duane|last5=Carrell|first5=Robin W.|last6=Coughlin|first6=Paul B.|date=1998|title=Angiotensinogen cleavage by renin: importance of a structurally constrained N-terminus|journal=FEBS Letters|volume=436|issue=2|pages=267\u2013270|doi=10.1016/S0014-5793(98)01145-4|pmid=9781693|issn=1873-3468}}</ref>\n\nAngiotensinogen is also known as renin substrate. It is cleaved at the N-terminus by renin to result in angiotensin I, which will later be modified to become angiotensin II.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> This peptide is 485 amino acids long, and 10 N-terminus amino acids are cleaved when renin acts on it.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first 12 amino acids are the most important for activity.\n\n:Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe-His-Leu-Val-Ile-...\n\nPlasma angiotensinogen levels are increased by plasma [[corticosteroid]], [[estrogen]], [[thyroid]] [[hormone]], and angiotensin II levels.\n\n=== Angiotensin I ===\n\n:Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe-His-Leu | Val-Ile-...\n\n[[Image:Renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.png|thumb|[[Renin\u2013angiotensin\u2013aldosterone system]]|480x480px]]\n\nAngiotensin I ([[CAS registry number|CAS]]# 11128-99-7), officially called '''proangiotensin''', is formed by the action of [[renin]] on [[angiotensinogen]]. Renin cleaves the [[peptide bond]] between the [[leucine]] (Leu) and [[valine]] (Val) residues on angiotensinogen, creating the [[Peptide#Notes on terminology|decapeptide]] (ten amino acid) (des-Asp) angiotensin I. Renin is produced in the [[kidney]]s in response to renal sympathetic activity, decreased intrarenal blood pressure (<90mmHg systolic blood pressure<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Preston RA, Materson BJ, Reda DJ, Williams DW, Hamburger RJ, Cushman WC, Anderson RJ | title = Age-race subgroup compared with renin profile as predictors of blood pressure response to antihypertensive therapy. Department of Veterans Affairs Cooperative Study Group on Antihypertensive Agents | journal = JAMA | volume = 280 | issue = 13 | pages = 1168\u201372 | date = October 1998 | pmid = 9777817 | doi = 10.1001/jama.280.13.1168 | doi-access = free }}</ref> ) at the [[juxtaglomerular cell]]s, or decreased delivery of Na+ and Cl- to the [[macula densa]].<ref name=\"isbn0-07-146633-9\">{{cite book |veditors=Loscalzo J, Fauci AS, Braunwald E, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL | title = Harrison's principles of internal medicine | edition = | publisher = McGraw-Hill Medical | location = | year = 2008 | origyear = | pages = | quote = | isbn = 978-0-07-146633-2 |vauthors=Williams GH, Dluhy RG | chapter = Chapter 336: Disorders of the Adrenal Cortex | accessdate = }}</ref>  If a reduced NaCl concentration<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Skott O, Briggs JP | year = 1987 | title = Direct demonstration of macula densa-mediated renin secretion | url = | journal = Science | volume = 237 | issue = 4822| pages = 1618\u20131620 | doi=10.1126/science.3306925| pmid = 3306925 | bibcode = 1987Sci...237.1618S }}</ref> in the distal tubule is sensed by the macula densa, renin release by juxtaglomerular cells is increased. This sensing mechanism for macula densa-mediated renin secretion appears to have a specific dependency on chloride ions rather than sodium ions. Studies using isolated preparations of [[thick ascending limb]] with [[Glomerulus (kidney)|glomerulus]] attached in low NaCl perfusate were unable to inhibit renin secretion when various sodium salts were added but could inhibit renin secretion with the addition of [[chloride]] salts.<ref name=\"pmid31796\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kirchner KA, Kotchen TA, Galla JH, Luke RG | title = Importance of chloride for acute inhibition of renin by sodium chloride | journal = The American Journal of Physiology | volume = 235 | issue = 5 | pages = F444\u201350 | date = November 1978 | pmid = 31796 | doi = 10.1152/ajprenal.1978.235.5.F444 }}</ref> This, and similar findings obtained in vivo,<ref name=\"pmid16303857\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kim SM, Mizel D, Huang YG, Briggs JP, Schnermann J | title = Adenosine as a mediator of macula densa-dependent inhibition of renin secretion | journal = American Journal of Physiology. Renal Physiology | volume = 290 | issue = 5 | pages = F1016\u201323 | date = May 2006 | pmid = 16303857 | doi = 10.1152/ajprenal.00367.2005 }}</ref> has led some to believe that perhaps \"the initiating signal for MD control of renin secretion is a change in the rate of NaCl uptake predominantly via a luminal [[Na-K-Cl cotransporter|Na,K,2Cl co-transporter]] whose physiological activity is determined by a change in luminal Cl concentration.\"<ref name=\"Schnermann_2013\">{{cite book | vauthors = Schnermann JB, Castrop H | chapter = Chapter 23: Function of the juxtaglomerular apparatus: control of glomerular hemodynamics and renin secretion. | pages = 757\u2013801 | veditors = Alpern RJ, Moe OW, Caplan M | title = Seldin and Giebisch's The Kidney | publisher = Academic Press | edition = Fifth | year = 2013 | isbn = 978-0-12-381462-3 | doi = 10.1016/B978-0-12-381462-3.00023-9 }}</ref>\n\nAngiotensin I appears to have no direct biological activity and exists solely as a precursor to angiotensin II.\n\n=== Angiotensin II ===\n{{see also|Angiotensin II (medication)}}\n\n:Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe\n\nAngiotensin I  is converted to angiotensin II (AII) through removal of two C-terminal residues by the enzyme ''[[angiotensin-converting enzyme]]'' (ACE), primarily through ACE within the lung (but also present in [[endothelial cells]], kidney epithelial cells, and the brain). Angiotensin II acts on the CNS to increase [[vasopressin]] production, and also acts on venous and arterial smooth muscle to cause vasoconstriction. Angiotensin II also increases [[aldosterone]] secretion; it therefore acts as an [[endocrine system|endocrine]], [[autocrine signalling|autocrine]]/[[paracrine signalling|paracrine]], and [[intracrine]] hormone.\n\nACE is a target of [[ACE inhibitor]] drugs, which decrease the rate of angiotensin II production. Angiotensin II increases blood pressure by stimulating the Gq protein in vascular smooth muscle cells (which in turn activates an IP3-dependent mechanism leading to a rise in intracellular calcium levels and ultimately causing contraction). In addition, angiotensin II acts at the [[Na+/H+ exchanger|Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup> exchanger]] in the [[proximal tubule]]s of the kidney to stimulate Na reabsorption and H<sup>+</sup> excretion which is coupled to bicarbonate reabsorption. This ultimately results in an increase in blood volume, pressure, and pH.<ref>{{cite book|last=Le|first=Tao | name-list-format = vanc |title=First Aid for the Basic Sciences. Organ Systems|year=2012|publisher=McGraw-Hill|page=625}}</ref> Hence, [[ACE inhibitor]]s are major anti-hypertensive drugs.\n\nOther cleavage products of ACE, seven or nine amino acids long, are also known; they have differential affinity for [[angiotensin receptors]], although their exact role is still unclear. The action of AII itself is targeted by [[angiotensin II receptor antagonist]]s, which directly block [[Angiotensin receptor|angiotensin II AT<sub>1</sub> receptors]].\n\nAngiotensin II is degraded to angiotensin III by angiotensinases located in red blood cells and the vascular beds of most tissues. It has a half-life in circulation of around 30 seconds, whereas, in tissue, it may be as long as 15\u201330 minutes.\n\nAngiotensin II results in increased inotropy, chronotropy, catecholamine (norepinephrine) release, catecholamine sensitivity, aldosterone levels, vasopressin levels, and cardiac remodeling and vasoconstriction through AT1 receptors on peripheral vessels (conversely, AT2 receptors impair cardiac remodeling). This is why ACE inhibitors and ARBs help to prevent remodeling that occurs secondary to angiotensin II and are beneficial in CHF.<ref name=\"Schnermann_2013\" />\n\n=== Angiotensin III ===\n\n:Asp | Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe\n\nAngiotensin III has 40% of the [[Vasoconstrictor|pressor]] activity of angiotensin II, but 100% of the aldosterone-producing activity.\nIncreases [[mean arterial pressure]]. It is a peptide that is formed by removing an amino acid from angiotensin II by aminopeptidase A <ref>{{cite web |url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/angiotensin_iii |title=Angiotensin III |website=PubChem |publisher=NIH |access-date= 9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Angiotensin IV ===\n\n:Arg | Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe\n\nAngiotensin IV is a hexapeptide that, like angiotensin III, has some lesser activity. Angiotensin IV has a wide range of activities in the central nervous system.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chai SY, Fernando R, Peck G, Ye SY, Mendelsohn FA, Jenkins TA, Albiston AL | title = The angiotensin IV/AT4 receptor | journal = Cellular and Molecular Life Sciences | volume = 61 | issue = 21 | pages = 2728\u201337 | date = November 2004 | pmid = 15549174 | doi = 10.1007/s00018-004-4246-1 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid19090988\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gard PR | title = Cognitive-enhancing effects of angiotensin IV | journal = BMC Neuroscience | volume = 9 Suppl 2 | issue =  | pages = S15 | date = December 2008 | pmid = 19090988 | pmc = 2604899 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2202-9-S2-S15 }}</ref>\n\nThe exact identity of AT4 receptors has not been established. There is evidence that the AT4 receptor is [[Leucyl/cystinyl aminopeptidase|insulin-regulated aminopeptidase]] (IRAP).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Albiston AL, McDowall SG, Matsacos D, Sim P, Clune E, Mustafa T, Lee J, Mendelsohn FA, Simpson RJ, Connolly LM, Chai SY | title = Evidence that the angiotensin IV (AT(4)) receptor is the enzyme insulin-regulated aminopeptidase | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 276 | issue = 52 | pages = 48623\u20136 | date = December 2001 | pmid = 11707427 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.C100512200 | doi-access = free }}</ref> There is also evidence that angiotensin IV interacts with the HGF system through the c-Met receptor.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wright JW, Harding JW | title = The Brain Hepatocyte Growth Factor/c-Met Receptor System: A New Target for the Treatment of Alzheimer's Disease | journal = Journal of Alzheimer's Disease | volume = 45 | issue = 4 | pages = 985\u20131000 | date = 2015-01-01 | pmid = 25649658 | doi = 10.3233/JAD-142814 }}</ref><ref name = \"Wright_2015\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wright JW, Kawas LH, Harding JW | title = The development of small molecule angiotensin IV analogs to treat Alzheimer's and Parkinson's diseases | journal = Progress in Neurobiology | volume = 125 | pages = 26\u201346 | date = February 2015 | pmid = 25455861 | doi = 10.1016/j.pneurobio.2014.11.004 }}</ref>\n\nSynthetic [[small molecule]] analogues of angiotensin IV with the ability to penetrate through [[blood brain barrier]] have been developed.<ref name = \"Wright_2015\" />\n\nThe AT4 site may be involved in memory acquisition and recall, as well as blood flow regulation.<ref name=\"pmid7768321\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wright JW, Krebs LT, Stobb JW, Harding JW | title = The angiotensin IV system: functional implications | journal = Frontiers in Neuroendocrinology | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 23\u201352 | date = January 1995 | pmid = 7768321 | doi = 10.1006/frne.1995.1002 }}</ref>\n\n== Effects ==<!--Renin\u2013angiotensin_system has a link to here-->\n:''See also [[Renin\u2013angiotensin system#Effects]]''\nAngiotensins II, III and IV have a number of effects throughout the body:\n\n=== Adipic ===\nAngiotensins \"modulate fat mass expansion through upregulation of adipose tissue lipogenesis ... and downregulation of lipolysis.\"<ref name=\"adipose review\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yvan-Charvet L, Quignard-Boulang\u00e9 A | title = Role of adipose tissue renin-angiotensin system in metabolic and inflammatory diseases associated with obesity | journal = Kidney International | volume = 79 | issue = 2 | pages = 162\u20138 | date = January 2011 | pmid = 20944545 | doi = 10.1038/ki.2010.391 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cardiovascular ===\n\nThey are potent direct [[vasoconstrictor]]s, constricting arteries and veins and increasing blood pressure. This effect is achieved through activation of the [[Angiotensin II receptor type 1|GPCR AT1]], which signals through a [[Gq alpha subunit|Gq protein]] to activate Phospholipase C, and subsequently increase intracellular calcium.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kanaide H, Ichiki T, Nishimura J, Hirano K | title = Cellular mechanism of vasoconstriction induced by angiotensin II: it remains to be determined | journal = Circulation Research | volume = 93 | issue = 11 | pages = 1015\u20137 | date = November 2003 | pmid = 14645130 | doi = 10.1161/01.RES.0000105920.33926.60 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nAngiotensin II has prothrombotic potential through adhesion and aggregation of [[platelets]] and stimulation of [[plasminogen activator inhibitor 1|PAI-1]] and [[plasminogen activator inhibitor 2|PAI-2]].<ref name=\"skurk\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Skurk T, Lee YM, Hauner H | title = Angiotensin II and its metabolites stimulate PAI-1 protein release from human adipocytes in primary culture | journal = Hypertension | volume = 37 | issue = 5 | pages = 1336\u201340 | date = May 2001 | pmid = 11358950 | doi = 10.1161/01.HYP.37.5.1336 | url = http://hyper.ahajournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11358950 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130112051812/http://hyper.ahajournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11358950 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2013-01-12 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"Gesualdo\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gesualdo L, Ranieri E, Monno R, Rossiello MR, Colucci M, Semeraro N, Grandaliano G, Schena FP, Ursi M, Cerullo G | title = Angiotensin IV stimulates plasminogen activator inhibitor-1 expression in proximal tubular epithelial cells | journal = Kidney International | volume = 56 | issue = 2 | pages = 461\u201370 | date = August 1999 | pmid = 10432384 | doi = 10.1046/j.1523-1755.1999.00578.x }}</ref>\n  \nWhen cardiac cell growth is stimulated, a local (autocrine-paracrine) renin\u2013angiotensin system is activated in the cardiac myocyte, which stimulates cardiac cell growth through protein kinase C. The same system can be activated in smooth muscle cells in conditions of hypertension, atherosclerosis, or endothelial damage. Angiotensin II is the most important Gq stimulator of the heart during hypertrophy, compared to endothelin-1 and \u03b11 adrenoreceptors.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n=== Neural ===\n\nAngiotensin II increases [[thirst]] sensation ([[dipsogen]]) through the [[area postrema]] and [[subfornical organ]] of the brain,<ref name=\"johnson\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Johnson AK, Gross PM | title = Sensory circumventricular organs and brain homeostatic pathways | journal = FASEB Journal | volume = 7 | issue = 8 | pages = 678\u201386 | date = May 1993 | pmid = 8500693 | doi=10.1096/fasebj.7.8.8500693}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Shaver SW, Kadekaro M, Gross PM | title = High metabolic activity in the dorsal vagal complex of Brattleboro rats | journal = Brain Research | volume = 505 | issue = 2 | pages = 316\u201320 | date = December 1989 | pmid = 2598049 | doi=10.1016/0006-8993(89)91459-5}}</ref><ref name=\"gross2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gross PM, Wainman DS, Shaver SW, Wall KM, Ferguson AV | title = Metabolic activation of efferent pathways from the rat area postrema | journal = The American Journal of Physiology | volume = 258 | issue = 3 Pt 2 | pages = R788-97 | date = March 1990 | pmid = 2316724 | doi = 10.1152/ajpregu.1990.258.3.R788 }}</ref> decreases the response of the [[baroreceptor reflex]], increases the desire for [[table salt|salt]], increases secretion of [[vasopressin|ADH]] from the [[posterior pituitary]], and increases secretion of [[corticotropin|ACTH]] from the [[anterior pituitary]].<ref name=johnson/> It also potentiates the release of [[norepinephrine]] by direct action on postganglionic [[sympathetic nervous system|sympathetic]] fibers.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n=== Adrenal ===\nAngiotensin II acts on the [[adrenal cortex]], causing it to release [[aldosterone]], a hormone that causes the kidneys to retain sodium and lose potassium. Elevated plasma angiotensin II levels are responsible for the elevated aldosterone levels present during the luteal phase of the [[menstrual cycle]].\n\n=== Renal ===\nAngiotensin II has a direct effect on the proximal tubules to increase Na<sup>+</sup> [[absorption (chemistry)|reabsorption]]. It has a complex and variable effect on [[glomerular filtration]] and [[renal blood flow]] depending on the setting. Increases in systemic blood pressure will maintain renal perfusion pressure; however, constriction of the afferent and efferent glomerular arterioles will tend to restrict renal blood flow. The effect on the efferent arteriolar resistance is, however, markedly greater, in part due to its smaller basal diameter; this tends to increase glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure and maintain [[glomerular filtration rate]]. A number of other mechanisms can affect renal blood flow and GFR. High concentrations of Angiotensin II can constrict the glomerular mesangium, reducing the area for glomerular filtration. Angiotensin II is a sensitizer to [[tubuloglomerular feedback]], preventing an excessive rise in GFR. Angiotensin II causes the local release of prostaglandins, which, in turn, antagonize renal vasoconstriction. The net effect of these competing mechanisms on glomerular filtration will vary with the physiological and pharmacological environment.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Direct Renal effects of angiotensin II (not including [[aldosterone]] release)\n|-\n!Target\n!Action\n!Mechanism<ref name=\"isbn1-4160-2328-3\">{{cite book |vauthors=Boulpaep EL, Boron WF | title = Medical Physiology: a Cellular and Molecular Approach | edition = | publisher = Elsevier Saunders | location = St. Louis, Mo | year = 2005 | origyear = | pages = 771 | quote = | isbn = 978-1-4160-2328-9 | oclc = | doi = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref>\n|-\n![[renal artery]] & <BR> [[afferent arterioles]] \n| [[vasoconstriction]] (weaker) || [[Voltage-dependent calcium channel|VDCC]]s \u2192 [[calcium|Ca<sup>2+</sup>]] influx\n|-\n! [[efferent arteriole]] \n| [[vasoconstriction]] (stronger) || (probably) activate [[Angiotensin receptor#AT1|Angiotensin receptor 1]] \u2192 Activation of [[gq alpha subunit|G<sub>q</sub>]] \u2192 \u2191[[phospholipase C|PLC]] activity \u2192 \u2191[[Inositol triphosphate|IP<sub>3</sub>]] and [[diacylglycerol|DAG]] \u2192 activation of [[Inositol triphosphate receptor|IP<sub>3</sub> receptor]] in [[sarcoplasmic reticulum|SR]] \u2192 \u2191intracellular Ca<sup>2+</sup> \n|-\n![[mesangial cell]]s \n| contraction \u2192 \u2193filtration area || \n* activation of [[gq alpha subunit|G<sub>q</sub>]] \u2192 \u2191[[phospholipase C|PLC]] activity \u2192 \u2191[[Inositol triphosphate|IP<sub>3</sub>]] and [[diacylglycerol|DAG]] \u2192 activation of [[Inositol triphosphate receptor|IP<sub>3</sub> receptor]] in [[sarcoplasmic reticulum|SR]] \u2192 \u2191intracellular Ca<sup>2+</sup>\n*[[Voltage-dependent calcium channel|VDCC]]s \u2192 [[calcium|Ca<sup>2+</sup>]] influx\n|-\n![[proximal tubule]]\n| increased Na<sup>+</sup> reabsorption ||\n* adjustment of [[Starling forces]] in peritubular capillaries to favour increased reabsorption\n** efferent and afferent arteriole contraction \u2192 decreased hydrostatic pressure in peritubular capillaries\n** efferent arteriole contraction \u2192 increased filtration fraction \u2192 increased colloid osmotic pressure in peritubular capillaries\n* increased [[sodium\u2013hydrogen antiporter]] activity\n|-\n! [[tubuloglomerular feedback]] \n| increased sensitivity || increase in [[afferent arteriole]] responsiveness to signals from [[macula densa]]\n|-\n! [[renal medulla|medullary]] blood flow \n| reduction ||\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[ACE inhibitor]]\n* [[Angiotensin receptor]]\n* [[Angiotensin II receptor antagonist]]\n* [[Captopril]]\n* [[Perindopril]]\n* [[Renin inhibitor]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin | 2}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = de Gasparo M, Catt KJ, Inagami T, Wright JW, Unger T | title = International union of pharmacology. XXIII. The angiotensin II receptors | journal = Pharmacological Reviews | volume = 52 | issue = 3 | pages = 415\u201372 | date = September 2000 | pmid = 10977869 }}\n*''Brenner & Rector's The Kidney'', 7th ed., Saunders, 2004.\n*''Mosby's Medical Dictionary'', 3rd Ed., CV Mosby Company, 1990.\n*''Review of Medical Physiology'', 20th Ed., William F. Ganong, McGraw-Hill, 2001.\n*''Clinical Physiology of Acid-Base and Electrolyte Disorders'', 5th ed., Burton David Rose & Theodore W. Post McGraw-Hill, 2001\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Lees KR, MacFadyen RJ, Doig JK, Reid JL | title = Role of angiotensin in the extravascular system | journal = Journal of Human Hypertension | volume = 7 Suppl 2 | issue =  | pages = S7-12 | date = August 1993 | pmid = 8230088 | doi =  }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Weir MR, Dzau VJ | title = The renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system: a specific target for hypertension management | journal = American Journal of Hypertension | volume = 12 | issue = 12 Pt 3 | pages = 205S\u2013213S | date = December 1999 | pmid = 10619573 | doi = 10.1016/S0895-7061(99)00103-X | doi-access = free }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Berry C, Touyz R, Dominiczak AF, Webb RC, Johns DG | title = Angiotensin receptors: signaling, vascular pathophysiology, and interactions with ceramide | journal = American Journal of Physiology. Heart and Circulatory Physiology | volume = 281 | issue = 6 | pages = H2337-65 | date = December 2001 | pmid = 11709400 | doi = 10.1152/ajpheart.2001.281.6.H2337 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Sernia C | title = A critical appraisal of the intrinsic pancreatic angiotensin-generating system | journal = Journal of the Pancreas | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = 50\u20135 | date = January 2001 | pmid = 11862023 | doi =  }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Varagic J, Frohlich ED | title = Local cardiac renin-angiotensin system: hypertension and cardiac failure | journal = Journal of Molecular and Cellular Cardiology | volume = 34 | issue = 11 | pages = 1435\u201342 | date = November 2002 | pmid = 12431442 | doi = 10.1006/jmcc.2002.2075 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Wolf G | title = Role of reactive oxygen species in angiotensin II-mediated renal growth, differentiation, and apoptosis | journal = Antioxidants & Redox Signaling | volume = 7 | issue = 9\u201310 | pages = 1337\u201345 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16115039 | doi = 10.1089/ars.2005.7.1337 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Cazaubon S, Deshayes F, Couraud PO, Nahmias C | title = [Endothelin-1, angiotensin II and cancer] | journal = M\u00e9decine/Sciences | volume = 22 | issue = 4 | pages = 416\u201322 | date = April 2006 | pmid = 16597412 | doi = 10.1051/medsci/2006224416 | doi-access = free }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Ariza AC, Bobadilla NA, Halhali A | title = [Endothelin 1 and angiotensin II in preeeclampsia] | journal = Revista de Investigacion Clinica; Organo del Hospital de Enfermedades de la Nutricion | volume = 59 | issue = 1 | pages = 48\u201356 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17569300 | doi =  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Angiotensin}}\n* The [[MEROPS]] online database for peptidases and their inhibitors: [http://merops.sanger.ac.uk/cgi-bin/merops.cgi?id=I04.953 I04.953]\n* {{MeshName|Angiotensins}}\n* {{UCSC gene info|AGT}}\n* {{PDBe-KB2|P01019|Angiotensin}}\n\n{{Cardiovascular physiology}}\n{{Neuropeptides}}\n{{Autacoids}}\n{{Angiotensin receptor modulators}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Peptide hormones]]\n[[Category:Angiology]]\n[[Category:Endocrinology]]\n[[Category:Hypertension]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox gene}}\n\n'''Angiotensin''' is a [[peptide hormone]] that causes [[vasoconstriction]] and an increase in [[blood pressure]]. It is part of the [[renin\u2013angiotensin system]], which regulates blood pressure. Angiotensin also stimulates the release of [[aldosterone]] from the [[adrenal cortex]] to promote sodium retention by the kidneys.\n\nAn [[peptide|oligopeptide]], angiotensin is a [[hormone]] and a [[dipsogen]]. It is derived from the precursor molecule angiotensinogen, a serum globulin produced in the [[liver]]. Angiotensin was isolated in the late 1930s (first named 'angiotonin' or 'hypertensin') and subsequently characterized and synthesized by groups at the [[Cleveland Clinic]] and [[Ciba Specialty Chemicals|Ciba]] laboratories.<ref name=\"pmid11751697\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Basso N, Terragno NA | title = History about the discovery of the renin-angiotensin system | journal = Hypertension | volume = 38 | issue = 6 | pages = 1246\u20139 | date = December 2001 | pmid = 11751697 | doi = 10.1161/hy1201.101214 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n== Precursor and types ==\n\n=== Angiotensinogen ===\nAngiotensinogen is an [[Alpha globulin|\u03b1-2-globulin]] synthesized in the liver<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hormone.org/your-health-and-hormones/glands-and-hormones-a-to-z/hormones/angiotensin|title=Angiotensin {{!}} Hormone Health Network|website=www.hormone.org|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> and is a precursor for angiotensin, but has also been indicated as having many other roles not related to angiotensin peptides.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=Hong|last2=Cassis|first2=Lisa A.|last3=Kooi|first3=Craig W. Vander|last4=Daugherty|first4=Alan|date=July 2016|title=Structure and functions of angiotensinogen|journal=Hypertension Research|volume=39|issue=7|pages=492\u2013500|doi=10.1038/hr.2016.17|pmid=26888118|pmc=4935807|issn=1348-4214}}</ref> It is a member of the serin family of proteins, leading to another name: Serin A8,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/P01019|title=AGT - Angiotensinogen precursor - Homo sapiens (Human) - AGT gene & protein|website=www.uniprot.org|access-date=2019-12-02}}</ref> although it is not known to inhibit other enzymes like most serins. In addition, a generalized crystal structure can be estimated by examining other proteins of the serin family, but angiotensinogen has an elongated N-terminus compared to other serin family proteins.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Streatfeild-James|first=Rosa M. A.|last2=Williamson|first2=David|last3=Pike|first3=Robert N.|last4=Tewksbury|first4=Duane|last5=Carrell|first5=Robin W.|last6=Coughlin|first6=Paul B.|date=1998|title=Angiotensinogen cleavage by renin: importance of a structurally constrained N-terminus|journal=FEBS Letters|volume=436|issue=2|pages=267\u2013270|doi=10.1016/S0014-5793(98)01145-4|pmid=9781693|issn=1873-3468}}</ref>\n\nAngiotensinogen is also known as renin substrate. It is cleaved at the N-terminus by renin to result in angiotensin I, which will later be modified to become angiotensin II.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> This peptide is 485 amino acids long, and 10 N-terminus amino acids are cleaved when renin acts on it.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first 12 amino acids are the most important for activity.\n\n:Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe-His-Leu-Val-Ile-...\n\nPlasma angiotensinogen levels are increased by plasma [[corticosteroid]], [[estrogen]], [[thyroid]] [[hormone]], and angiotensin II levels.\n\n=== Angiotensin I ===\n\n:Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe-His-Leu | Val-Ile-...\n\n[[Image:Renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.png|thumb|[[Renin\u2013angiotensin\u2013aldosterone system]]|480x480px]]\n\nAngiotensin I ([[CAS registry number|CAS]]# 11128-99-7), officially called '''proangiotensin''', is formed by the action of [[renin]] on [[angiotensinogen]]. Renin cleaves the [[peptide bond]] between the [[leucine]] (Leu) and [[valine]] (Val) residues on angiotensinogen, creating the [[Peptide#Notes on terminology|decapeptide]] (ten amino acid) (des-Asp) angiotensin I. Renin is produced in the [[kidney]]s in response to renal sympathetic activity, decreased intrarenal blood pressure (<90mmHg systolic blood pressure<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Preston RA, Materson BJ, Reda DJ, Williams DW, Hamburger RJ, Cushman WC, Anderson RJ | title = Age-race subgroup compared with renin profile as predictors of blood pressure response to antihypertensive therapy. Department of Veterans Affairs Cooperative Study Group on Antihypertensive Agents | journal = JAMA | volume = 280 | issue = 13 | pages = 1168\u201372 | date = October 1998 | pmid = 9777817 | doi = 10.1001/jama.280.13.1168 | doi-access = free }}</ref> ) at the [[juxtaglomerular cell]]s, or decreased delivery of Na+ and Cl- to the [[macula densa]].<ref name=\"isbn0-07-146633-9\">{{cite book |veditors=Loscalzo J, Fauci AS, Braunwald E, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL | title = Harrison's principles of internal medicine | edition = | publisher = McGraw-Hill Medical | location = | year = 2008 | origyear = | pages = | quote = | isbn = 978-0-07-146633-2 |vauthors=Williams GH, Dluhy RG | chapter = Chapter 336: Disorders of the Adrenal Cortex | accessdate = }}</ref>  If a reduced NaCl concentration<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Skott O, Briggs JP | year = 1987 | title = Direct demonstration of macula densa-mediated renin secretion | url = | journal = Science | volume = 237 | issue = 4822| pages = 1618\u20131620 | doi=10.1126/science.3306925| pmid = 3306925 | bibcode = 1987Sci...237.1618S }}</ref> in the distal tubule is sensed by the macula densa, renin release by juxtaglomerular cells is increased. This sensing mechanism for macula densa-mediated renin secretion appears to have a specific dependency on chloride ions rather than sodium ions. Studies using isolated preparations of [[thick ascending limb]] with [[Glomerulus (kidney)|glomerulus]] attached in low NaCl perfusate were unable to inhibit renin secretion when various sodium salts were added but could inhibit renin secretion with the addition of [[chloride]] salts.<ref name=\"pmid31796\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kirchner KA, Kotchen TA, Galla JH, Luke RG | title = Importance of chloride for acute inhibition of renin by sodium chloride | journal = The American Journal of Physiology | volume = 235 | issue = 5 | pages = F444\u201350 | date = November 1978 | pmid = 31796 | doi = 10.1152/ajprenal.1978.235.5.F444 }}</ref> This, and similar findings obtained in vivo,<ref name=\"pmid16303857\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kim SM, Mizel D, Huang YG, Briggs JP, Schnermann J | title = Adenosine as a mediator of macula densa-dependent inhibition of renin secretion | journal = American Journal of Physiology. Renal Physiology | volume = 290 | issue = 5 | pages = F1016\u201323 | date = May 2006 | pmid = 16303857 | doi = 10.1152/ajprenal.00367.2005 }}</ref> has led some to believe that perhaps \"the initiating signal for MD control of renin secretion is a change in the rate of NaCl uptake predominantly via a luminal [[Na-K-Cl cotransporter|Na,K,2Cl co-transporter]] whose physiological activity is determined by a change in luminal Cl concentration.\"<ref name=\"Schnermann_2013\">{{cite book | vauthors = Schnermann JB, Castrop H | chapter = Chapter 23: Function of the juxtaglomerular apparatus: control of glomerular hemodynamics and renin secretion. | pages = 757\u2013801 | veditors = Alpern RJ, Moe OW, Caplan M | title = Seldin and Giebisch's The Kidney | publisher = Academic Press | edition = Fifth | year = 2013 | isbn = 978-0-12-381462-3 | doi = 10.1016/B978-0-12-381462-3.00023-9 }}</ref>\n\nAngiotensin I appears to have no direct biological activity and exists solely as a precursor to angiotensin II.\n\n=== Angiotensin II ===\n{{see also|Angiotensin II (medication)}}\n\n:Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe\n\nAngiotensin I  is converted to angiotensin II (AII) through removal of two C-terminal residues by the enzyme ''[[angiotensin-converting enzyme]]'' (ACE), primarily through ACE within the lung (but also present in [[endothelial cells]], kidney epithelial cells, and the brain). Angiotensin II acts on the CNS to increase [[vasopressin]] production, and also acts on venous and arterial smooth muscle to cause vasoconstriction. Angiotensin II also increases [[aldosterone]] secretion; it therefore acts as an [[endocrine system|endocrine]], [[autocrine signalling|autocrine]]/[[paracrine signalling|paracrine]], and [[intracrine]] hormone.\n\nACE is a target of [[ACE inhibitor]] drugs, which decrease the rate of angiotensin II production. Angiotensin II increases blood pressure by stimulating the Gq protein in vascular smooth muscle cells (which in turn activates an IP3-dependent mechanism leading to a rise in intracellular calcium levels and ultimately causing contraction). In addition, angiotensin II acts at the [[Na+/H+ exchanger|Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup> exchanger]] in the [[proximal tubule]]s of the kidney to stimulate Na reabsorption and H<sup>+</sup> excretion which is coupled to bicarbonate reabsorption. This ultimately results in an increase in blood volume, pressure, and pH.<ref>{{cite book|last=Le|first=Tao | name-list-format = vanc |title=First Aid for the Basic Sciences. Organ Systems|year=2012|publisher=McGraw-Hill|page=625}}</ref> Hence, [[ACE inhibitor]]s are major anti-hypertensive drugs.\n\nOther cleavage products of ACE, seven or 9 amino acids long, are also known; they have differential affinity for [[angiotensin receptors]], although their exact role is still unclear. The action of AII itself is targeted by [[angiotensin II receptor antagonist]]s, which directly block [[Angiotensin receptor|angiotensin II AT<sub>1</sub> receptors]].\n\nAngiotensin II is degraded to angiotensin III by angiotensinases located in red blood cells and the vascular beds of most tissues. It has a half-life in circulation of around 30 seconds, whereas, in tissue, it may be as long as 15\u201330 minutes.\n\nAngiotensin II results in increased inotropy, chronotropy, catecholamine (norepinephrine) release, catecholamine sensitivity, aldosterone levels, vasopressin levels, and cardiac remodeling and vasoconstriction through AT1 receptors on peripheral vessels (conversely, AT2 receptors impair cardiac remodeling). This is why ACE inhibitors and ARBs help to prevent remodeling that occurs secondary to angiotensin II and are beneficial in CHF.<ref name=\"Schnermann_2013\" />\n\n=== Angiotensin III ===\n\n:Asp | Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe\n\nAngiotensin III has 40% of the [[Vasoconstrictor|pressor]] activity of angiotensin II, but 100% of the aldosterone-producing activity.\nIncreases [[mean arterial pressure]]. It is a peptide that is formed by removing an amino acid from angiotensin II by aminopeptidase A <ref>{{cite web |url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/angiotensin_iii |title=Angiotensin III |website=PubChem |publisher=NIH |access-date= 9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Angiotensin IV ===\n\n:Arg | Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe\n\nAngiotensin IV is a hexapeptide that, like angiotensin III, has some lesser activity. Angiotensin IV has a wide range of activities in the central nervous system.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chai SY, Fernando R, Peck G, Ye SY, Mendelsohn FA, Jenkins TA, Albiston AL | title = The angiotensin IV/AT4 receptor | journal = Cellular and Molecular Life Sciences | volume = 61 | issue = 21 | pages = 2728\u201337 | date = November 2004 | pmid = 15549174 | doi = 10.1007/s00018-004-4246-1 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid19090988\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gard PR | title = Cognitive-enhancing effects of angiotensin IV | journal = BMC Neuroscience | volume = 9 Suppl 2 | issue =  | pages = S15 | date = December 2008 | pmid = 19090988 | pmc = 2604899 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2202-9-S2-S15 }}</ref>\n\nThe exact identity of AT4 receptors has not been established. There is evidence that the AT4 receptor is [[Leucyl/cystinyl aminopeptidase|insulin-regulated aminopeptidase]] (IRAP).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Albiston AL, McDowall SG, Matsacos D, Sim P, Clune E, Mustafa T, Lee J, Mendelsohn FA, Simpson RJ, Connolly LM, Chai SY | title = Evidence that the angiotensin IV (AT(4)) receptor is the enzyme insulin-regulated aminopeptidase | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 276 | issue = 52 | pages = 48623\u20136 | date = December 2001 | pmid = 11707427 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.C100512200 | doi-access = free }}</ref> There is also evidence that angiotensin IV interacts with the HGF system through the c-Met receptor.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wright JW, Harding JW | title = The Brain Hepatocyte Growth Factor/c-Met Receptor System: A New Target for the Treatment of Alzheimer's Disease | journal = Journal of Alzheimer's Disease | volume = 45 | issue = 4 | pages = 985\u20131000 | date = 2015-01-01 | pmid = 25649658 | doi = 10.3233/JAD-142814 }}</ref><ref name = \"Wright_2015\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wright JW, Kawas LH, Harding JW | title = The development of small molecule angiotensin IV analogs to treat Alzheimer's and Parkinson's diseases | journal = Progress in Neurobiology | volume = 125 | pages = 26\u201346 | date = February 2015 | pmid = 25455861 | doi = 10.1016/j.pneurobio.2014.11.004 }}</ref>\n\nSynthetic [[small molecule]] analogues of angiotensin IV with the ability to penetrate through [[blood brain barrier]] have been developed.<ref name = \"Wright_2015\" />\n\nThe AT4 site may be involved in memory acquisition and recall, as well as blood flow regulation.<ref name=\"pmid7768321\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wright JW, Krebs LT, Stobb JW, Harding JW | title = The angiotensin IV system: functional implications | journal = Frontiers in Neuroendocrinology | volume = 16 | issue = 1 | pages = 23\u201352 | date = January 1995 | pmid = 7768321 | doi = 10.1006/frne.1995.1002 }}</ref>\n\n== Effects ==<!--Renin\u2013angiotensin_system has a link to here-->\n:''See also [[Renin\u2013angiotensin system#Effects]]''\nAngiotensins II, III and IV have a number of effects throughout the body:\n\n=== Adipic ===\nAngiotensins \"modulate fat mass expansion through upregulation of adipose tissue lipogenesis ... and downregulation of lipolysis.\"<ref name=\"adipose review\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Yvan-Charvet L, Quignard-Boulang\u00e9 A | title = Role of adipose tissue renin-angiotensin system in metabolic and inflammatory diseases associated with obesity | journal = Kidney International | volume = 79 | issue = 2 | pages = 162\u20138 | date = January 2011 | pmid = 20944545 | doi = 10.1038/ki.2010.391 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cardiovascular ===\n\nThey are potent direct [[vasoconstrictor]]s, constricting arteries and veins and increasing blood pressure. This effect is achieved through activation of the [[Angiotensin II receptor type 1|GPCR AT1]], which signals through a [[Gq alpha subunit|Gq protein]] to activate Phospholipase C, and subsequently increase intracellular calcium.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kanaide H, Ichiki T, Nishimura J, Hirano K | title = Cellular mechanism of vasoconstriction induced by angiotensin II: it remains to be determined | journal = Circulation Research | volume = 93 | issue = 11 | pages = 1015\u20137 | date = November 2003 | pmid = 14645130 | doi = 10.1161/01.RES.0000105920.33926.60 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nAngiotensin II has prothrombotic potential through adhesion and aggregation of [[platelets]] and stimulation of [[plasminogen activator inhibitor 1|PAI-1]] and [[plasminogen activator inhibitor 2|PAI-2]].<ref name=\"skurk\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Skurk T, Lee YM, Hauner H | title = Angiotensin II and its metabolites stimulate PAI-1 protein release from human adipocytes in primary culture | journal = Hypertension | volume = 37 | issue = 5 | pages = 1336\u201340 | date = May 2001 | pmid = 11358950 | doi = 10.1161/01.HYP.37.5.1336 | url = http://hyper.ahajournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11358950 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130112051812/http://hyper.ahajournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11358950 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2013-01-12 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"Gesualdo\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gesualdo L, Ranieri E, Monno R, Rossiello MR, Colucci M, Semeraro N, Grandaliano G, Schena FP, Ursi M, Cerullo G | title = Angiotensin IV stimulates plasminogen activator inhibitor-1 expression in proximal tubular epithelial cells | journal = Kidney International | volume = 56 | issue = 2 | pages = 461\u201370 | date = August 1999 | pmid = 10432384 | doi = 10.1046/j.1523-1755.1999.00578.x }}</ref>\n  \nWhen cardiac cell growth is stimulated, a local (autocrine-paracrine) renin\u2013angiotensin system is activated in the cardiac myocyte, which stimulates cardiac cell growth through protein kinase C. The same system can be activated in smooth muscle cells in conditions of hypertension, atherosclerosis, or endothelial damage. Angiotensin II is the most important Gq stimulator of the heart during hypertrophy, compared to endothelin-1 and \u03b11 adrenoreceptors.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n\n=== Neural ===\n\nAngiotensin II increases [[thirst]] sensation ([[dipsogen]]) through the [[area postrema]] and [[subfornical organ]] of the brain,<ref name=\"johnson\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Johnson AK, Gross PM | title = Sensory circumventricular organs and brain homeostatic pathways | journal = FASEB Journal | volume = 7 | issue = 8 | pages = 678\u201386 | date = May 1993 | pmid = 8500693 | doi=10.1096/fasebj.7.8.8500693}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Shaver SW, Kadekaro M, Gross PM | title = High metabolic activity in the dorsal vagal complex of Brattleboro rats | journal = Brain Research | volume = 505 | issue = 2 | pages = 316\u201320 | date = December 1989 | pmid = 2598049 | doi=10.1016/0006-8993(89)91459-5}}</ref><ref name=\"gross2\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gross PM, Wainman DS, Shaver SW, Wall KM, Ferguson AV | title = Metabolic activation of efferent pathways from the rat area postrema | journal = The American Journal of Physiology | volume = 258 | issue = 3 Pt 2 | pages = R788-97 | date = March 1990 | pmid = 2316724 | doi = 10.1152/ajpregu.1990.258.3.R788 }}</ref> decreases the response of the [[baroreceptor reflex]], increases the desire for [[table salt|salt]], increases secretion of [[vasopressin|ADH]] from the [[posterior pituitary]], and increases secretion of [[corticotropin|ACTH]] from the [[anterior pituitary]].<ref name=johnson/> It also potentiates the release of [[norepinephrine]] by direct action on postganglionic [[sympathetic nervous system|sympathetic]] fibers.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n=== Adrenal ===\nAngiotensin II acts on the [[adrenal cortex]], causing it to release [[aldosterone]], a hormone that causes the kidneys to retain sodium and lose potassium. Elevated plasma angiotensin II levels are responsible for the elevated aldosterone levels present during the luteal phase of the [[menstrual cycle]].\n\n=== Renal ===\nAngiotensin II has a direct effect on the proximal tubules to increase Na<sup>+</sup> [[absorption (chemistry)|reabsorption]]. It has a complex and variable effect on [[glomerular filtration]] and [[renal blood flow]] depending on the setting. Increases in systemic blood pressure will maintain renal perfusion pressure; however, constriction of the afferent and efferent glomerular arterioles will tend to restrict renal blood flow. The effect on the efferent arteriolar resistance is, however, markedly greater, in part due to its smaller basal diameter; this tends to increase glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure and maintain [[glomerular filtration rate]]. A number of other mechanisms can affect renal blood flow and GFR. High concentrations of Angiotensin II can constrict the glomerular mesangium, reducing the area for glomerular filtration. Angiotensin II is a sensitizer to [[tubuloglomerular feedback]], preventing an excessive rise in GFR. Angiotensin II causes the local release of prostaglandins, which, in turn, antagonize renal vasoconstriction. The net effect of these competing mechanisms on glomerular filtration will vary with the physiological and pharmacological environment.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Direct Renal effects of angiotensin II (not including [[aldosterone]] release)\n|-\n!Target\n!Action\n!Mechanism<ref name=\"isbn1-4160-2328-3\">{{cite book |vauthors=Boulpaep EL, Boron WF | title = Medical Physiology: a Cellular and Molecular Approach | edition = | publisher = Elsevier Saunders | location = St. Louis, Mo | year = 2005 | origyear = | pages = 771 | quote = | isbn = 978-1-4160-2328-9 | oclc = | doi = | url = | accessdate = }}</ref>\n|-\n![[renal artery]] & <BR> [[afferent arterioles]] \n| [[vasoconstriction]] (weaker) || [[Voltage-dependent calcium channel|VDCC]]s \u2192 [[calcium|Ca<sup>2+</sup>]] influx\n|-\n! [[efferent arteriole]] \n| [[vasoconstriction]] (stronger) || (probably) activate [[Angiotensin receptor#AT1|Angiotensin receptor 1]] \u2192 Activation of [[gq alpha subunit|G<sub>q</sub>]] \u2192 \u2191[[phospholipase C|PLC]] activity \u2192 \u2191[[Inositol triphosphate|IP<sub>3</sub>]] and [[diacylglycerol|DAG]] \u2192 activation of [[Inositol triphosphate receptor|IP<sub>3</sub> receptor]] in [[sarcoplasmic reticulum|SR]] \u2192 \u2191intracellular Ca<sup>2+</sup> \n|-\n![[mesangial cell]]s \n| contraction \u2192 \u2193filtration area || \n* activation of [[gq alpha subunit|G<sub>q</sub>]] \u2192 \u2191[[phospholipase C|PLC]] activity \u2192 \u2191[[Inositol triphosphate|IP<sub>3</sub>]] and [[diacylglycerol|DAG]] \u2192 activation of [[Inositol triphosphate receptor|IP<sub>3</sub> receptor]] in [[sarcoplasmic reticulum|SR]] \u2192 \u2191intracellular Ca<sup>2+</sup>\n*[[Voltage-dependent calcium channel|VDCC]]s \u2192 [[calcium|Ca<sup>2+</sup>]] influx\n|-\n![[proximal tubule]]\n| increased Na<sup>+</sup> reabsorption ||\n* adjustment of [[Starling forces]] in peritubular capillaries to favour increased reabsorption\n** efferent and afferent arteriole contraction \u2192 decreased hydrostatic pressure in peritubular capillaries\n** efferent arteriole contraction \u2192 increased filtration fraction \u2192 increased colloid osmotic pressure in peritubular capillaries\n* increased [[sodium\u2013hydrogen antiporter]] activity\n|-\n! [[tubuloglomerular feedback]] \n| increased sensitivity || increase in [[afferent arteriole]] responsiveness to signals from [[macula densa]]\n|-\n! [[renal medulla|medullary]] blood flow \n| reduction ||\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[ACE inhibitor]]\n* [[Angiotensin receptor]]\n* [[Angiotensin II receptor antagonist]]\n* [[Captopril]]\n* [[Perindopril]]\n* [[Renin inhibitor]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin | 2}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = de Gasparo M, Catt KJ, Inagami T, Wright JW, Unger T | title = International union of pharmacology. XXIII. The angiotensin II receptors | journal = Pharmacological Reviews | volume = 52 | issue = 3 | pages = 415\u201372 | date = September 2000 | pmid = 10977869 }}\n*''Brenner & Rector's The Kidney'', 7th ed., Saunders, 2004.\n*''Mosby's Medical Dictionary'', 3rd Ed., CV Mosby Company, 1990.\n*''Review of Medical Physiology'', 20th Ed., William F. Ganong, McGraw-Hill, 2001.\n*''Clinical Physiology of Acid-Base and Electrolyte Disorders'', 5th ed., Burton David Rose & Theodore W. Post McGraw-Hill, 2001\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Lees KR, MacFadyen RJ, Doig JK, Reid JL | title = Role of angiotensin in the extravascular system | journal = Journal of Human Hypertension | volume = 7 Suppl 2 | issue =  | pages = S7-12 | date = August 1993 | pmid = 8230088 | doi =  }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Weir MR, Dzau VJ | title = The renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system: a specific target for hypertension management | journal = American Journal of Hypertension | volume = 12 | issue = 12 Pt 3 | pages = 205S\u2013213S | date = December 1999 | pmid = 10619573 | doi = 10.1016/S0895-7061(99)00103-X | doi-access = free }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Berry C, Touyz R, Dominiczak AF, Webb RC, Johns DG | title = Angiotensin receptors: signaling, vascular pathophysiology, and interactions with ceramide | journal = American Journal of Physiology. Heart and Circulatory Physiology | volume = 281 | issue = 6 | pages = H2337-65 | date = December 2001 | pmid = 11709400 | doi = 10.1152/ajpheart.2001.281.6.H2337 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Sernia C | title = A critical appraisal of the intrinsic pancreatic angiotensin-generating system | journal = Journal of the Pancreas | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = 50\u20135 | date = January 2001 | pmid = 11862023 | doi =  }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Varagic J, Frohlich ED | title = Local cardiac renin-angiotensin system: hypertension and cardiac failure | journal = Journal of Molecular and Cellular Cardiology | volume = 34 | issue = 11 | pages = 1435\u201342 | date = November 2002 | pmid = 12431442 | doi = 10.1006/jmcc.2002.2075 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Wolf G | title = Role of reactive oxygen species in angiotensin II-mediated renal growth, differentiation, and apoptosis | journal = Antioxidants & Redox Signaling | volume = 7 | issue = 9\u201310 | pages = 1337\u201345 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16115039 | doi = 10.1089/ars.2005.7.1337 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Cazaubon S, Deshayes F, Couraud PO, Nahmias C | title = [Endothelin-1, angiotensin II and cancer] | journal = M\u00e9decine/Sciences | volume = 22 | issue = 4 | pages = 416\u201322 | date = April 2006 | pmid = 16597412 | doi = 10.1051/medsci/2006224416 | doi-access = free }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Ariza AC, Bobadilla NA, Halhali A | title = [Endothelin 1 and angiotensin II in preeeclampsia] | journal = Revista de Investigacion Clinica; Organo del Hospital de Enfermedades de la Nutricion | volume = 59 | issue = 1 | pages = 48\u201356 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17569300 | doi =  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Angiotensin}}\n* The [[MEROPS]] online database for peptidases and their inhibitors: [http://merops.sanger.ac.uk/cgi-bin/merops.cgi?id=I04.953 I04.953]\n* {{MeshName|Angiotensins}}\n* {{UCSC gene info|AGT}}\n* {{PDBe-KB2|P01019|Angiotensin}}\n\n{{Cardiovascular physiology}}\n{{Neuropeptides}}\n{{Autacoids}}\n{{Angiotensin receptor modulators}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Peptide hormones]]\n[[Category:Angiology]]\n[[Category:Endocrinology]]\n[[Category:Hypertension]]\n", "name_user": "RexxS", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAngiotensin II:MOS:NUM", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angiotensin"}
{"title_page": "Ensiferum", "text_new": "{{One source|article|date=May 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Ensiferum\n| image            = Ensiferum Rockharz 2016 08.jpg\n| caption          = Sami Hinkka and Petri Lindroos with Ensiferum at Rockharz festival 2016 in [[Germany]]\n| image_size       = 250\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Folk metal]]\n* [[melodic death metal]]\n* [[power metal]]\n* [[Viking metal]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 1995\u2013present\n| label            = [[Spinefarm Records|Spinefarm]], [[Metal Blade Records|Metal Blade]]\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Wintersun]], [[Arthemesia]]|[[Cadacross]]|[[Chthonic (band)|Chthonic]]|[[Norther]]|[[Waltari]]|[[Sinergy]]|[[Turisas]]}}\n| website          = {{url|www.ensiferum.com}}\n| current_members  = [[Markus Toivonen]]<br />[[Petri Lindroos]]<br />[[Sami Hinkka]]<br />[[Janne Parviainen]]<br />[[ Pekka Montin]]\n| past_members     = Sauli Savolainen<br />Kimmo Miettinen<br />[[Jari M\u00e4enp\u00e4\u00e4]]<br />Oliver Fokin<br />Jukka-Pekka Miettinen<br />[[Meiju Enho]]<br />[[Emmi Silvennoinen]]<br />Netta Skog\n}}\n\n'''Ensiferum''' (Latin [[:wikt:ensifer|''\u0113nsiferum'']], n adj., meaning \"sword bearing\") is a Finnish [[folk metal]]<!-- See WP:Lead for word usage at the start of articles. It is to generalize the genres as a whole and not to be used as a descriptor. --> band from [[Helsinki]]. The members of the band label themselves as \"melodic folk metal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Ensiferum/info|title=Ensiferum - About|website=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=December 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Band history==\n===Formation, demos and ''Ensiferum'' (1995\u22122002)===\n''Ensiferum'' was founded in 1995 by [[Markus Toivonen]] ([[guitar]]), Sauli Savolainen (bass) and Kimmo Miettinen (drums). For the band's name, they took the [[Latin]]  adjective ''ensiferum'', which means \"sword-bearing\". In the next year, [[Jari M\u00e4enp\u00e4\u00e4]] was taken into the band as singer and second guitar-player. In 1997, the first demo was released, containing three songs.\n\n[[File:Ensiferum (logo).svg|180px|thumb|right|The highly stylized logo of Ensiferum has appeared on all of their releases.]]\n[[File:Ensiferum Rockharz 2016 25.jpg|thumb|Guitarist Markus Toivonen at Rockharz 2016]]\n[[File:Ensiferum Rockharz 2016 23.jpg|thumb|Accordeonista Netta Skog at Rockharz 2016]]\nIn 1998, Sauli and Kimmo left the band and were replaced by Jukka-Pekka Miettinen (Kimmo's little brother, then 14 years old) and Oliver Fokin. In January 1999, a second demo was recorded, which although it did not produce a recording deal, boosted the band's confidence. In November 1999 a third demo, \"Hero in a Dream\", was recorded, which was successful in obtaining a record deal with [[Spinefarm Records]]. The logo that appears on all the bands releases was designed for the third demo by Tuomas Tahvanainen, who also designed the logos for the earlier demos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ensiferum.com/e_html/e_history.htm|title=Story of Ensiferum|website=Ensiferum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113121556/http://www.ensiferum.com/e_html/e_history.htm|archivedate=January 13, 2008|accessdate=January 25, 2008}}</ref> In 2000, the band went into the studio to work on their first album, ''[[Ensiferum (album)|Ensiferum]]'', which was released in August 2001. In the same year, Meiju Enho joined them as a [[Synthesizer|keyboard]]-player.\n\n===''Iron'', Line-up changes, ''Dragonheads'' and ''10th Anniversary Live'' (2003\u22122006)===\nIn 2004, after the work was completed on the second album, ''[[Iron (Ensiferum)|Iron]]'', Jari left the band due to conflicts between scheduled studio work on his side project [[Wintersun]] and touring with Ensiferum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tartareandesire.com/interviews/wintersun.html|title=Wintersun interview|website=Tartarean Desire Webzine|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011072155/https://www.tartareandesire.com/interviews/wintersun.html|archive-date=October 11, 2017|access-date=November 30, 2019}}</ref> For the tour with [[Finntroll]], Petri Lindroos from [[Norther]] replaced Jari on guitar and as singer, and became a member of the band after the tour. In December 2004, Jukka-Pekka left the band and was replaced by Sami Hinkka ([[Rapture (band)|Rapture]]). Oliver also left in 2005 to be replaced by Janne Parviainen.\n\nThe new Ensiferum line-up entered the studio later that year to record an [[Extended play|EP]] to be called ''[[Dragonheads]]'', which was released in February 2006. As well as the title track, it also contained two reworked demo songs; an [[Amorphis]] cover and a short rendition of the [[Kalevala]] melody, as well as a medley of three traditional [[Finland|Finnish]] songs.\n\nIn June 2006, Ensiferum released their live [[DVD]], ''[[10th Anniversary Live]]'', which was recorded in [[Nosturi]], [[Helsinki]], on 31 December 2005.\n\n===''Victory Songs'' and Meiju's departure (2006\u22122009)===\nThe recording of the third studio album, called ''[[Victory Songs]]'', took place between November 2006 and early 2007, and was released on 20 April 2007. A single titled \"[[One More Magic Potion]]\" (after the track of the same name) was released on 7 February. Following the album's release, the band released through the producer's [[MySpace]] page, a music video for the song \"Ahti,\" which included all band members featured as extras. The video was released after the album release due to video filming problems.\n\nOn 10 September 2007, it was announced that keyboardist [[Meiju Enho]] would leave the band. This was posted in a bulletin on their MySpace page and later confirmed on their website. The band used [[Emmi Silvennoinen]] of [[Exsecratus]] as a touring fill-in.  She later became a permanent member of the band during the recording of the From Afar album.<ref name=\"past\" /><ref name=\"future\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ensiferum.com/e_html/e_news.htm|title=Ensiferum \u2014 Latest News|website=Ensiferum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104082210/http://ensiferum.com/e_html/e_news.htm|archivedate=January 4, 2010|accessdate=August 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nEnsiferum headlined the Paganfest tour in Europe and North America in 2008.<ref name=\"past\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ensiferum.com/e_html/e_tourinfo_old.htm|title=Ensiferum \u2014 Concert history|website=Ensiferum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225065609/http://www.ensiferum.com/e_html/e_tourinfo_old.htm|archivedate=February 25, 2009|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref> Others playing the tour included [[T\u00fdr (band)|T\u00fdr]] and [[Eluveitie]], with [[Moonsorrow]] and [[Korpiklaani]] also joining them on the European part of the tour, and [[Turisas]] in North America.<ref name=\"past\" /> They also supported [[Megadeth]] on the opening night of their [[United Abominations|United Abominations \u2013 Tour of Duty]] European tour.<ref name=\"past\" /> Ensiferum also supported [[Amon Amarth]] on their North American ''[[Twilight of the Thunder God]]'' tour.<ref name=\"past\" />\n\nShortly before their Russian tour in 2008, vocalist/guitarist Petri Lindroos fell \"seriously ill\" and was unable to participate. The band hired ex-bassist Jukka-Pekka Miettinen to assume Lindroos' guitar duties, while bassist Sami Hinkka took over his lead vocal duties for the tour.\n\nIn the first half of 2009, Ensiferum performed at a string of [[metal festival|festivals]] including Frostrock in [[Belgium]], [[Finnish Metal Expo]] and [[Tuska Open Air]] in [[Finland]], Winterfire, Rocktower, Legacy and Rock am H\u00e4rtsfeldsee in [[Germany]], Summer Nights in [[Austria]], and Z7 Metal Dayz in [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"past\" /> In June and July they toured North America as part of the [[Summer Slaughter Tour]] with [[Necrophagist]], [[Darkest Hour (band)|Darkest Hour]], [[Suffocation (band)|Suffocation]], Blackguard, [[Dying Fetus]], [[Beneath the Massacre]], [[Origin (band)|Origin]], and [[Winds of Plague]].<ref name=\"past\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ensiferum.com/e_html/e_tourinfo.htm|title=Ensiferum \u2014 Future concerts|website=Ensiferum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418060737/http://ensiferum.com/e_html/e_tourinfo.htm|archivedate=April 18, 2009|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref> In August they performed at the Global East Rock Festival in [[Ukraine]], [[Ankkarock]] and Jurassic Rock in [[Finland]], and Let's Open Air in [[Turkey]].<ref name=\"future\" />\n\n=== ''From Afar and Unsung Heroes'' (2009\u22122012) ===\nEnsiferum released their fourth [[studio album]], ''[[From Afar (album)|From Afar]]'', on 9 September 2009 with [[Spinefarm Records]]. The album was produced by [[Nightwish]] producer [[Tero Kinnunen]] and ''[[Victory Songs]]'' producer Janne Joutsenniemi, and it was mixed by producer [[Hiili Hiilesmaa]].<ref name=\"news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ensiferum.com/e_html/e_news.htm|title=Ensiferum \u2014 News|website=Ensiferum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104082210/http://ensiferum.com/e_html/e_news.htm|archivedate=January 4, 2010|accessdate=July 2, 2009}}</ref> The limited edition of the album includes a cover of [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[folk rock]] group [[Nordman]] with guest vocalist [[Heri Joensen]] of Faroese band [[T\u00fdr (band)|T\u00fdr]].<ref name=\"from-afar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=122903|title=Ensiferum: new album title, track listing revealed|date=July 1, 2009|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 2, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703130022/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=122903|archivedate=July 3, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gjpfdN8NX5E|title=Ensiferum Interview With Peter Lindroos @ Ankkarock 2009|date=August 16, 2009|website=[[YouTube]]|access-date=November 30, 2019}}</ref> Following the release, the group embarked on a European tour with [[Estonia]]n [[folk metal]] band [[Metsat\u00f6ll]] and [[Finland|Finnish]] [[melodic death metal]] band [[Tracedawn]].<ref name=\"future\" /><ref name=\"news\" /><ref name=\"from-afar\" /> In October they performed at Hellflame Festival \u2013 The South Side of Hell and Devil's Revenge festival in [[Germany]], and Tattoo the Mind in [[France]].<ref name=\"future\" /> Ensiferum performed on the second day of the inaugural Screamfest Festival in Sydney, Australia, on New Years Day 2010. In November/December they toured North America with Ex Deo (on selected dates), and Blackguard.\n\nEnsiferum were also confirmed to play [[Bloodstock Open Air]] at Catton Hall, United Kingdom in 2010. In October 2010, Ensiferum embarked on their first ever South African tour. This tour consisted of four shows in two cities, and they were accompanied by numerous local metal bands including [[Riddare av Koden]], Empery and All Forlorn. The final show, at The Black Dahlia in Johannesburg, was filmed to potentially appear on their next live DVD. In early 2011 Ensiferum embarked on [[The Ugly World Tour 2011]] with labelmates [[Children of Bodom]], [[Amon Amarth]], [[Machinae Supremacy]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} supporting them for segments of their tour in the US and Canada. The tour took place within a 4-month period of time and spanned 23 countries.\n\nThe band's fifth studio album, [[Unsung Heroes (Ensiferum album)|''Unsung Heroes'']], was released on 24 August 2012; this would be their final album for Spinefarm Records. The next year, Ensiferum signed with [[Metal Blade Records]] after thirteen years with their previous label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalblade.com/us/news/ensiferum-sign-to-metal-blade-records/|title=ENSIFERUM sign worldwide deal with Metal Blade Records|date=April 24, 2013|website=[[Metal Blade Records]]|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> After release of the album, Ensiferum embarked on a tour of Europe and South America. \n\n=== New Label, ''One Man Army'', and ''Two Paths'' (2013\u2212Onward) ===\nEnsiferum's sixth album, [[One Man Army (Ensiferum album)|''One Man Army'']], was released on 20 February 2015. The album was recorded at Astia Studio with producer [[Anssi Kippo]]. A music video for the title track \"One Man Army\" was released prior to the album's release. In March of that year, Ensiferum announced on their Facebook page that keyboardist Emmi Silvennoinen would not be able to make the European and North American \"One Man Army Tour\" due to personal commitments at home. Former [[Turisas]] accordion player Netta Skog filled her role for the tour. Skog had performed clean vocals on the ''One Man Army'' songs ''Cry for the Earth Bounds'' and ''Neito Pohjolan''. [[Heri Joensen]] of [[T\u00fdr (band)|T\u00fdr]] makes an appearance on the track \"Heathen Horde\", quoting stanza 16 of ''H\u00e1vam\u00e1l'' in Old Icelandic.\n\nOn 31 March 2016 it was announced that Emmi Silvennoinen would take a leave of absence from the band because of personal issues. Netta Skog was confirmed as her permanent replacement. With Skog in the line-up, the band entered the studio to record their seventh studio album, ''[[Two Paths (album)|Two Paths]]''. Anssi Kippo, who had produced ''One Man Army'', was again chosen to produce the album. The band focused on a more \"organic\" sound for ''Two Paths'', using [[analog recording]] and neglecting to use a [[click track]] for certain songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ensiferum.com/band/|title=Band \u2013 Ensiferum|website=Ensiferum|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> ''Two Paths'' was released on 15 September 2017.\n\nAccordionist Netta Skog left the band in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Ensiferum/posts/10155249567326309|title=NETTA SKOG TO LEAVE ENSIFERUM|date=December 21, 2017|website=[[Facebook]]|access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Eighth Album ===\nOn January 7th, 2020, the band announced that they had begun recording a follow up record to ''Two Paths'', at Studio Petrax in [[Hollola]], Finland. This release coincides with the band's 25th anniversary.\n\n==Musical style==\nThe band has been described as [[folk metal]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/ensiferum-mw0000462283|title=Ensiferum - Ensiferum {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|last=Rivadavia|first=Eduardo|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=August 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/iron-mw0000746753|title=Iron - Ensiferum {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|last=Rivadavia|first=Eduardo|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=August 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ensiferum-mn0000629036/biography|title=Ensiferum {{!}} Biography & History|last=Rivadavia|first=Eduardo|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=November 30, 2019}}</ref> [[melodic death metal]],<ref name=\"AM\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/victory-songs-mw0000486350|title=Victory Songs - Ensiferum {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|last=Henderson|first=Alex|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=June 13, 2009}}</ref> [[power metal]]<ref name=\"AM\" /> and [[Viking metal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/wintersun-mn0000786354/biography|title=Wintersun {{!}} Biography & History|last=Rivadavia|first=Eduardo|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=November 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n\n===Current members===\n* [[Markus Toivonen]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitars, backing vocals <small>(1995\u2013present)</small>, clean vocals <small>(2004\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Petri Lindroos]]&nbsp;\u2013 harsh vocals, guitars <small>(2004\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Sami Hinkka]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass, clean vocals <small>(2004\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Janne Parviainen]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums <small>(2005\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Pekka Montin]]&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards, clean vocals <small>(2020\u2013present)</small>\n\n<gallery perrow=\"4\" caption=\"Ensiferum, Line-Up at Rockharz Open Air 2018\">\nFile:Ensiferum Rockharz 2018 12.jpg|Guitarist Markus Toivonen\nFile:Ensiferum Rockharz 2018 14.jpg|Singer Petri Lindroos\nFile:Ensiferum Rockharz 2018 13.jpg|Bassist Sami Hinkka\nFile:Ensiferum Rockharz 2018 11.jpg|Drummer Janne Parviainen \n</gallery>\n\n===Former members===\n* Sauli Savolainen&nbsp;\u2013 bass <small>(1995\u20131998)</small>\n* Kimmo Miettinen&nbsp;\u2013 drums <small>(1995\u20131998)</small>\n* [[Jari M\u00e4enp\u00e4\u00e4]]&nbsp;\u2013 harsh & clean vocals, guitars <small>(1996\u20132004)</small>\n* Jukka-Pekka Miettinen&nbsp;\u2013 bass <small>(1998\u20132004)</small>\n* Oliver Fokin&nbsp;\u2013 drums <small>(1998\u20132005)</small>\n* [[Meiju Enho]]&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards <small>(2001\u20132007)</small>\n* [[Emmi Silvennoinen]]&nbsp;\u2013 keyboards, backing vocals <small>(2007\u20132016)</small>\n* Netta Skog&nbsp;\u2013 electric accordion, backing vocals <small>(2016\u20132017)</small>\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:130 bottom:60 top:0 right:40\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1995 till:{{#time: m/d/Y }}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:1\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:1995\nScaleMinor = increment:2 start:1996\n\nColors =\n id:vocals   value:red      legend:Vocals\n id:guitar   value:green    legend:Guitar\n id:keyboard value:purple   legend:Keyboards\n id:accordion value:magenta legend:Accordion\n id:bass     value:blue     legend:Bass\n id:drums    value:orange   legend:Drums\n id:lines    value:black    legend:Studio_Albums\n id:other   value:gray(0.5)  legend:Other_Releases\n\nLineData =\n  at:01/07/2001 color:black layer:back\n  at:05/17/2004 color:black layer:back\n  at:04/2